<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ericsson Denies Mobile Phone-Cancer Connection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Ericsson, Sweden's
telecommunications giant, today ruled out the possibility of link
between mobile phones and cancer.
</P>
<P>
An Ericsson-published brochure said, "there is no scientific
proof of a connection between mobile phones and cancer."
</P>
<P>
Some researchers have raised the question that low-level
radiation from cellular phones can cause brain tumors or damage to
genetic material.
</P>
<P>
There also exists concern that the radio waves from the phone's
antenna can have a warming effect, which can cause cancer.
</P>
<P>
The brochure said that low-energy Ericsson cell-phones have a
maximum effect comparable to a small flashlight.
</P>
<P>
"Scientific tests have shown that a long telephone conversation
can't increase body temperature by more than 0.1 degree
Celsius. This effect is insignificant compared to normal
variations of body temperature," it concluded.
</P>
<P>
However, Lars Ramqvist, chief executive of the company, said,
"Ericsson will continue to conduct independent research in this
field because it is of great importance to the industry and the
public." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
