<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Considers Linking Dirham to Other Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
is considering linking its U.S. dollar-pegged currency dirham to a
basket of currencies, a senior UAE official said today.
</P>
<P>
"There will be serious thought about linking the dirham to a
basket of currencies," UAE's Minister of State for Financial and
Industry Affairs Hohammed Khalfan bin Kharbash said at a meeting
held in Dubai, one of the seven emirates of the country.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has blamed a 13-billion-dollar trade loss between 1986
and 1994 on its currency's linkage to the dollar. The exchange
rate stands at one dollar against 3.65 dirhams and this has
remained unchanged for years.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister said that the change of currency links
needs coordination at the level of the Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) member states, which also include Saudi Arabia, Oman, Qatar,
Bahrain and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The GCC has debated over the past decade the move to hook their
currency units to a basket of currencies but failed to reach a
consensus.
</P>
<P>
Except Kuwait, which pegged its dinar to a basket of
currencies, the GCC members denominated their oil prices only in
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The oil-rich states' economies are heavily reliant on the
prices of crude oil, which brings them billions of dollars in
revenue each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
