<HEADLINE> No Re-introduction of Death Penalty in S. Africa: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Zhao Yi)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 29 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela reiterated today that his government will not
re-introduce capital punishment in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Court held that the death penalty is
unconstitutional, Mandela told a meeting of the National Council
of Province.
</P>
<P>
"It is not easy for the government to ignore the considered
view of such a tribunal," he added.
</P>
<P>
South Africa abolished capital punishment on the eve of the
first non-racial general elections in 1994. The maximum of the
punishment for offenders has degraded to life imprisonment since
then.
</P>
<P>
However, as violent activities and vicious crimes are
increasing in South Africa, about half of blacks and more than 60
percent of whites have demanded for re-introduction of death
penalty in hope to curb the crimes.
</P>
<P>
In response to the viewpoint, Mandela pointed out that death
penalty was the most cruel and ruthless way of persecution
against the black people in apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
Punishments short of death penalty still can make offenders
repent, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
