<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's SADC/COMESA Membership Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe will continue with its
dual membership of the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) and the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa
(COMESA) until the SADC trade protocol is ratified by all
members, a senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
Beatrice Mtetwa, Deputy Secretary of the Industry and Commerce
Ministry, said while COMESA had made significant strides in
reducing trade barriers, Zimbabwe could not afford to relinquish
its membership of SADC which was strongly moving toward a free
trade zone.
</P>
<P>
''While it might take time to see benefits from the SADC trade
protocol, we will continue to belong to both organisations
because the SADC agreement considers other areas that are not
considered under COMESA,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
She noted that among other issues, the SADC trade protocol,
signed in Lesotho last year, also sought to foster cross-border
investment and institutional development.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, intra-COMESA trade is attracting 20 percent
duty while the qualitative and quantitative barriers vary
depending on a number of bilateral agreements that exist within
the region.
</P>
<P>
She challenged the local business community to capitalise on
the opportunities ushered in by the opening up of regional
markets by strengthening their competitive advantages through
investment in skills development.
</P>
<P>
These comments followed the reservations by some
industrialists who questioned the benefits of the country's dual
membership of COMESA and SADC, which groups 12 countries in
southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Under the SADC trade protocol, yet to be ratified by 10 of the
member states, the region seeks to create a free trade area by
the year 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
