<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police in Nepali Town Asked to Control Stray Bulls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The municipality of Nepalgunj
in mid-western Nepal had to ask the police to help control stray
bulls that butt people causing one death, obstruct traffic and
damage crops, the official RSS news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Traffic policemen in the town have been rounding up stray cows
but turned a blind eye to the bulls, which are considered sacred
in Hindu Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The religious belief has it that bulls left at large under the
invocation of the Trisul or Trident, a symbol of sea god or
supremacy, should continue to be left at large.
</P>
<P>
Recently a stray bull butted a man and he later died.
</P>
<P>
And every year some 20 people are injured by such bulls, the
RSS said.
</P>
<P>
In Nepali cities and towns, stray bulls are left to roam at
will. Anyone who kills or injures them has to pay fines and serve
terms in jail.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
