<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African Trade Unions Urged to Combat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Participants at the seminar on
child labor today urged trade unions in southern African countries
to take a leading role in combating child labor.
</P>
<P>
The two-day workshop which opens here today is attended by
more than 50 delegates from African countries.
</P>
<P>
The participants said since most workers are poorly paid, they
encourage their children to take up jobs at early ages and
supplement family income.
</P>
<P>
It is, therefore, the duty of trade unions to fight for better
remuneration for their members and reverse the situation.
</P>
<P>
"Most workers in the lower income brackets encourage their
children to seek employment at tender ages because their income
is not adequate to provide education, food and clothing for the
children," the participants said.
</P>
<P>
Geir Myrstad, International Labor Organization chief technical
advisor on child labor, urged trade unions to use collective
bargaining as a tool to fight child labor.
</P>
<P>
"Through collective bargaining, trade unions promote social
justice and a living wage, thereby weakening the dependence of
poor families on the income of their children," he said.
</P>
<P>
Myrstad called on trade unions to set up permanent structures
to deal with child labor.
</P>
<P>
The participants urged governments of south African countries
to help set up income generating projects and increase the
number of adults who earn an income in the family. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
