<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Signs More Contracts with Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has signed new trade
contracts with Syria worth 30 million U.S. dollars, according to a
press release here today.
</P>
<P>
The deal on the import of big quantities of legumes and soap
from Syria via the Natf border checkpoint brought the total value
of Iraqi contracts with Syria signed under the U.N.-Iraqi
oil-for-food deal to 50 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
On June 8, Iraq inked deals with Syria on the import of 20,000
tonnes of wheat and 10,000 tonnes of lentil at a value of 20
million dollars
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Trade Ministry revealed today at the press release
that it signed contracts on the purchase of 650,000 tonnes of
wheat from the United States, Australia and France in addition to
quantities of rice from Thailand, Vietnam, China and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
It had brought from four U.S. firms 100,000 tonnes of wheat,
50,000 tonnes of sugar and 18,000 tonnes of white beans with a
total value of 70 million dollars during the first phase of the
oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal, Iraq is allowed to export 2
billion dollars worth of oil over a renewed six month period to
buy food and other humanitarian goods for its people who have
been suffering under U.N.-imposed sanctions following Iraqi
invasion of Kuwait in August 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
