<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More US Workers Feel Less Secure About Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 29 (Xinhua) -- More than two-thirds of U.S.
workers say their sense of job security is lower and job stress
higher than it used to be, according to a new survey.
</P>
<P>
This is despite the best economic conditions in a generation
and a 4.8 percent jobless rate, the tightest job market in 25
years, according to Friday's USA TODAY, which carried the survey.
</P>
<P>
Seventy percent of workers surveyed by Princeton Survey
Research Associates said they have less job security than 20 or 30
years ago. And 73 percent say there's more on-the-job stress. The
survey also shows that 59 percent of workers say they have to work
harder to earn a decent living.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the nationwide poll was conducted for State of
the Union, a four-part series produced by PBS with the
participation of USA TODAY.
</P>
<P>
The powerful economic turnaround has done little to erase
insecurity among the nation's 130 million workers, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Corporate downsizing and restructuring that was common earlier
this decade left workers feeling less secure, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
Corporate mergers and downsizings were blamed by 61 percent
of workers for holding wages down. Other findings include: 33
percent work more than 45 hours a week, up from 27 percent six
years ago. Those who work 60 hours a week or more held at 12
percent. Part-timers, who work less than 35 hours a week, were
steady at 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
A big part of the insecurity is caused by the vast
technological changes in the workplace, according to Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
