<HEADLINE> Egyptian Delegation Promotes Peace Talks in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 29 (Xinhua)-- A four-member Egyptian
delegation led by Marwan Badri, Assistant Foreign Secretary for
African Affairs, today met the North Mogadishu authorities
in the divided Somali capital, Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The delegation crossed the green line dividing the capital
following their extensive talks with Hussein Mohamed Aidid and
his senior officials in South Mogadishu yesterday.
</P>
<P>
There has been no official statement released by Hussein
Aidid's faction over the Egyptian delegation's visit nor talks
between them.
</P>
<P>
However, sources close to the headquarters of Hussein Aidid
revealed that the Egyptian diplomats are on a mission
to persuade the South Mogadishu authorities to attend a national
reconciliation conference to be held in Cairo as agreed by
Hussein Aidid himself and his arch rival, Ali Mahdi Mohamed about
three months ago.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the Egyptian efforts are not concurrent with
the anticipated Bossaso conference in November for the factions
which established the National Salvation Council in Sodere,
Ethiopia early this year.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian initiative is suggesting another reconciliation
conference for the Somali factions which would preferably be held
in Cairo, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The delegation landed in Somalia two days ago is expected to
fly tomorrow on their way to visit Somaliland for similar
purposes, they added.
</P>
<P>
But they noted that Mohamed Ibrahim Egal, self-styled
president of the break away Republic of Somaliland, is less
likely to accept any conference with the participation of the
rest of the Somali faction leaders.
</P>
<P>
Both Egypt and Italy seem to be campaigning for the convening
of a new national reconciliation conference with different venues
than Bossaso which would be eligible for all the concerned
parties including Hussein Mohamed Aidid.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Hussein Aidid and Italy are preferring regional
level reconciliations to any national level conference, an idea
strongly opposed by the Sodere factions in Ethiopia and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
This political stalemate will further prolong the anarchy and
civil war that ravaged Somalia for the past seven years,
observers here say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
