<HEADLINE> Heyns Beaten Again in Universiade Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MESSINA, Sicily, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The only world-class swimmer
in the Universiade Penelope Heyns was beaten again on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Heyns, the world record holder and Olympic champion, lost in her
speciality of women's 100 meters breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
Also the holder of Universiade record, Heynsswam only 1:10.15 for
the silver medal. The result was 3.13 seconds off her world record.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Heyns finished a disappointing fourth in the women's
200 meter breaststroke final.
</P>
<P>
Svtlana Bondarenko of Ukraine won the gold of the 100 meters
breaststroke at 1:10.02 while Dagmara Ajnenkiel of Poland finished
third at 1:10.70.
</P>
<P>
Denis Silantev gave Ukraine the second swimming gold of the day by
winning the men's 100 meters butterfly final at 53.73 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The women's 100 meters freestyle gold went to Martina Moravcova of
Slovakia who clocked a winning time of 55.47 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Another East European swimmer Anna Urymiuk from Poland claimed the
women's 200 meters butterfly title after beating her Japanese opponent
Mika Haruna with a time of 2:13.58.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time since the beginning of the Universiade
swimming tournament that Japanese swimmers failed to win a gold. They
only got one silver and one bronze on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the last three days, Japanese swimmers dominated the
competitions by taking seven gold medals.
</P>
<P>
The Americans kept winning in the relay events. On Friday, the
American team took the gold of the men's 4X100 meters freestyle relay
at 3:21.17. It was their fourth relay title.
</P>
<P>
The men's 400 meters freestyle title was taken by Brazilian Luiz
Eduardo Lima.
</P>
<P>
Lima, who led the morning's preliminaries, clocked 3:53.91 for the
title. Bela Szabados of Hungary finished second at 3:54.30 and Hisato
Yasui of Japan took the bronze with 3:55.05. 
</P>
