<HEADLINE> Mauritian President Appeals for Africa's Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 29 (Xinhua) --Visiting Mauritian President
Cassim Uteem today called on the international community to help
boost Africa's economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
" There is more need now for the international community to
help boost africa's economic and social development," President
Cassim Uteem said.
</P>
<P>
Opening the Zimbabwe agricultural show, he said although the
continent was blessed with an array of natural resources, some of
the countries are still grappling with a lot of problems such as
low per capita incomes.
</P>
<P>
''The pace of development has not yet reached the right
momentum,'' said Uteem, adding, ''It is an undeniable fact that
the paths taken by these economies have been shaped to a great
extent by policies and strategies chalked out by colonial rulers
in the past.''
</P>
<P>
Africans should not allow themselves to fall into the trap of
believing that Africa is only the images of savage and
wanton killings and images of conflict, death, disease and
disaster, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said most African countries are now reaping the fruits of
democratisation, political pluralism and stability, economic
reform and tranquility.
</P>
<P>
The major problem facing this third world continent is
the lack of resources to exploit its untapped wealth and
potential, he said.
</P>
<P>
The president also emphasised the need for
regional integration to enable Africa to compete strongly in
the world market.
</P>
<P>
Uteem arrived here on Monday for six-day official visit to
Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
