<HEADLINE> European Shares down on Weak Wall Street, Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
continued their downward trend and ended lower again today, still
depressed by heavy falls in New York and Asia.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index finished 0.6 percent lower, its weakest
close for five weeks, but trimmed losses as the Dow regained its
footing following an early tumble.
</P>
<P>
Turmoil in the Far East hit sentiment in London after the Hang
Seng index plunged by around 4 percent for a second day. Stocks
exposed to Asia led the market lower, with the FTSE 100 index
falling 27.9 points at 4,817.5 by the close of the session, 83.6
points down on the week.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt ended 1.7 percent down in thin
trading, with overnight Wall Street losses and a softer dollar
weighing on the market.
</P>
<P>
The DAX-30 index closed 67.62 points down at 3,906.03, a fall
of 179.98 points from last Friday. Earlier the index had plunged
to 3,863.
</P>
<P>
Stocks on the Paris bourse failed to retake the key 2,800 level
as weak US equities and interest rate jitters overshadowed
stronger French bonds. The CAC-40 index finished down 57.92 points
at 2,770.49, 133.74 points lower on the week. 
</P>
