<HEADLINE> Kenya, IMF Agree on Conditions for Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) said today it has reached mutual understanding with the
Kenyan government on a series of conditions under which
negotiations on a lapsed IMF key loan can re-start.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here, Goodall Gondwe, Deputy Director of
IMF African Department, said that the IMF-Kenyan talks were
fruitful and "constructive".
</P>
<P>
He said IMF-Kenyan negotiations would be held provided that
Kenya improve management of the energy sector, safeguard the
independence of the revenue authority, set up an independent and
powerful anti-graft body and ensure accountability and
transparency in public finance.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, the Kenyan government said in a statement it
had reiterated to the IMF its commitment to making concrete
measures to solve these problems as soon as possible to pave the
way for resuming negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"The reaction of the domestic financial markets to the lapse
of the first-year ESAF (Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility)
arrangement demonstrates clearly the need for the underlying
concerns to be addressed," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Gondwe said his team "will convey the program of measures to
the Fund's management for determination of whether they would be
sufficient to initiate a second annual ESAF arrangement."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he stressed the suspension of the three-year
215-million-U.S.-Dollar IMF aid package should not be seen as "a
punishment" but just a guarantee for all resources to be properly
used in the country.
</P>
<P>
Kenya "has undertaken a lot of reforms" and made significant
economic progress in the past four years, he said, noting that
the IMF-Kenyan relations "are very close and will continue" and
not be broken down over the loan cut.
</P>
<P>
Gondwe and his team came to this east African country last
Saturday at the invitation of Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi.
</P>
<P>
The team held talks with Moi and other senior Kenyan officials
in the Indian Ocean port city Mombasa and capital Nairobi from
last Saturday to today.
</P>
<P>
IMF halted the loan package on July 31, citing high-level
corruption and bad governance. The move caused panics on Kenyan
stock and foreign exchange markets during the past month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
