<HEADLINE> Taylor Favors Talks in Solving S. Leone Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Liberia's new President Charles
Taylor, whose country just emerged from a seven-year civil war,
has joined the growing number of countries which are in favor of
a dialogue for the resolution of the Sierra Leone crisis.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the experiences of his country, where the
factional fightings were ended with the help of a sub-regional
peace-keeping force, Taylor said, "the problem in Liberia was not
resolved by the threat or the use of force."
</P>
<P>
"Rather, its mitigation emerged from trust, personal
commitment, and the understanding and neutrality of our host
sister state," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Taylor was speaking at the opening Friday of the 20th summit
of the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), which
is scheduled to close today.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the basis for the sub-region to evolve a
common approach to the crisis should be the Harare declaration of
the Organization of African Unity against the May 25 coup in
Sierra Leone and the final communique of the Conakry
extraordinary meeting of the ECOWAS ministers on June 26.
</P>
<P>
However, he urged the sub-regional leaders, who had agreed on
a three-pronged approach to resolve the crisis -- dialogue,
sanctions and force, to be judicious and "weigh with objective
scrutiny the inescapable practical realities on the ground".
</P>
<P>
Taylor, whose reservation for military option is shared by
Ghana, Togo and Senegal, said however, "We should be seen as
acting with a firm resolution, showing tolerance for our
differences of opinion, while respecting the territorial
integrity and sovereignty of each member state."
</P>
<P>
With regard to the peace-keeping force in his country, known
as ECOMOG, Taylor called for the revision of its mandate from
peace-keeping to providing security and capacity building for
national security.
</P>
<P>
He also called for the re-conceptualization of the force as a
regional peace-keeping force for future conflicts so that its
role would reflect the peculiarity of each conflict.
</P>
<P>
Taylor, whose country is faced with post-war reconstruction
and rehabilitation, urged the sub-regional leaders to lead the
crusade for the lifting of the international embargo against
Liberia which was imposed during the seven years of civil war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
