<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-29 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Egyptians, First Human to Master Weaving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 29 (Xinhua) -- An unprecedented archaeological
find has confirmed that ancient Egyptians mastered weaving 7,000
years ago, local Arabic newspaper Al Akhbar reported today.
</P>
<P>
This would put the ancient Egyptians undisputedly the first
human beings to use textile, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
An excavation carried out recently by Egypt's Supreme
Archaeological Council (SAC) discovered three unique clay boats
and a linen scroll dating back to the pre-dynasty age, i.e. more
than 5,000 years B.C., in the Awlad Dawood Hill, East Delta
governorate, about 150 kilometers northeast of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Some remains of human bones were also found with linen shrouds
and covered with a mat of the same period, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
These excavations indicated that the ancient Egyptians had known
weaving for at least seven millennia, even before the invention of
writing, the paper quoted SAC Secretary General Ali Hassan as
saying.
</P>
<P>
More exciting about the recent discovery is that the unearthed
boats have no equivalent in the history of the Egyptian
civilization, he added.
</P>
<P>
The bow and the stern of a first boat resemble the shape of a
hedgehog, the symbol of Atom, the God of Sun. The second boat has
decorations in the form of ostriches while the third has a common
shape.
</P>
<P>
Along with a string of potteries painted in red that date back
to the early dynasty period, the excavation also discovered
mummies of a 0.75-meter-high child and a 1.20-meter-high man, as
well as seven copper needles that are thought to be used in
mummification.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the discovery will shed light on the
intricate skills used by ancient Egyptian in preserving human
bodies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Steps Up Deporting Illegal Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
deporting illegal aliens at a record pace this year, partly
because of a get-tough immigration law passed last year, the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS) said.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary figures show that 75,743 had been formally deported
during the nine-month period that ended June 30, already exceeding
the 68,871 deported in the 12-month period that ended September
30, 1996, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
More than 32,200 people were deported from April through June,
the agency said, including about 40 percent with criminal records.
</P>
<P>
The numbers don't include the more than 57,000 aliens who left
the country without being formally deported. Most chose to leave
voluntarily after they were caught.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of criminal aliens deported had committed
offenses that were classified as aggravated felonies under
immigration law. Drug convictions accounted for more than 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 immigration law helped drive up the number of
noncriminal removals 64 percent, INS officials said.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, aliens arriving at U.S. airports and other ports
of entry without proper documents are refused entry into the
country "unless there is a credible asylum claim or a claim to
permanent resident status," the INS said.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 law that took effect on April 1 raised the standard
aliens have to meet in order to apply for asylum and has led to
about 10,000 removals, the INS said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
