<HEADLINE> Turkish Islamists Protest Educational Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 29 (Xinhua) -- A large crowd of conservative
Islamists staged a rally today in Turkey's largest city of
Istanbul to protest the lately approved eight-year compulsory
education law.
</P>
<P>
The protesters, mostly bearded young men showing defiance,
gathered around the Beyazit Mosque to demonstrate following the
regular Friday prayer service, the semi-official Anatolia News
Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Reinforcement had to be dispatched to the scene to assist
security police already there, reports said, adding that the
protesters finally dispersed without clash with police.
</P>
<P>
Today's demonstration was the continuation of a series of
protests lodged by conservative Islamists every Friday to protest
the recently passed education law.
</P>
<P>
The law initiated by the government led by Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz demands that students finish eight years of compulsory
education before they are permitted to start religious studies,
leading to the closure of many religious schools.
</P>
<P>
Police on Thursday detained 18 people accused of organizing
Friday protests around the mosques in major cities, especially in
Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
The secular government's education reform program is aimed at
stemming the rapidly growing fundamentalism in the country, which
was unleashed by the pro-Islamic policies adopted by former Prime
Minister Necmettin Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan, who was forced to resign in June under the pressure
from the military and pro-secularists, vowed to appeal to the
Constitutional Court to have the new education annulled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
