<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn to Allow Bugging of Apartments to Combat Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The German government today said
that it is planning to allow police to bug apartments of suspected
criminals as a measure to help crack down the country's rising
crimes.
</P>
<P>
Legal experts representing the German government and the main
opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) had agreed on a planned
constitutional change to allow police to use bugging devices to
gather information from homes of people suspected of being
involved in violent or organized crimes, Bonn officials said.
</P>
<P>
Under current laws, German police have been barred from bugging
activities, except in rare cases to prevent a crime or to save the
lives of hostages.
</P>
<P>
The new constitutional change must be approved with a
two-thirds majority in both houses of parliament. With the support
of most of Germany's 16 federal states and the SPD, which controls
the upper house of parliament, observers said the new law was
likely to be approved swiftly and take effect within this year.
</P>
<P>
According to government figures quoted by the German news
agency DPA, the number of registered violent crimes in Germany
rose by 5.5 percent in 1996. The number of organized crimes was
also on the rise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
