<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Home Sales in U.S. Up 0.9 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 29 (Xinhua) -- New home sales in the U.S.
rose by 0.9 percent in July, the third straight monthly advance,
U.S. commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that sales of single-family homes in July
totaled a seasonally adjusted 817,000 annual rate, up from a
revised 810,000 in June.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, sales of new homes shot up 11 percent in the West.
But they fell by 5.1 percent in the Midwest, 4.3 percent in the
Northeast and 2.5 percent in the South.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the seasonally adjusted estimate of new
homes for sale at the end of July was 287,000, unchanged from June
and representing a supply of 4.3 months at the current sales pace.
</P>
<P>
The inventory level is considered low and analysts said that it
could provide incentives to builders to continue laying
foundations.
</P>
<P>
The median price of a new home in the U.S was 146,700 dollars
in July, up from 143,800 dollars in June and 144,200 dollar a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
For the first seven months of the year, sales of new homes in
the U.S. were 7.4 percent above those of the same period a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
Analysts are expecting housing activity to level off during the
remainder of the year but say job and income growth and relatively
low mortgage rates will keep housing starts and sales near their
current levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
