<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Consumer Spending Increases Quickly in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Consumer spending in the U.S.
shot up by 0.8 percent in July, the biggest jump in six months,
U.S. commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that consumer spending totaled 5.49
trillion dollars at a seasonally adjusted annual rate in July, up
from 5.44 trillion dollars in June. The increase was the biggest
since a 1.1 percent gain in last January.
</P>
<P>
Consumption of durable goods, items expected to last more than
three years, jumped 1.9 percent, faster than June's 0.4 percent
gain. Motor vehicles accounted for most of the July advance.
</P>
<P>
Spending on nondurable goods such as food and fuel and on
services such as health care both rose 0.6 percent after
increasing 0.2 percent a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
The report was closely examined by economists and the financial
markets because consumer spending represents two-thirds of the
nation's economic activity. Analyst have seen signs that the U.S.
economy may be growing too fast to avoid a fresh bout of
inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department also reported that personal income rose
just 0.1 percent, the smallest gain since last October.
</P>
<P>
It said that incomes totaled 6.87 trillion dollars at an annual
rate in July, up from 6.86 trillion in June.
</P>
<P>
Private wages and salaries, the most closely watched component
of income, fell 3 billion dollars in the month after rising 30.3
billion in June. Average weekly hours also declined, more than
offsetting an increase in jobs.
</P>
<P>
Disposable income -- income after taxes -- edged up 0.1
percent, the smallest increase since a similar gain in April.
</P>
<P>
The combination of incomes and spending meant that Americans'
savings rate -- savings as a percentage of disposable income --
was 3.7 percent in July compared with 4.3 percent a month earlier,
lowest since a similar rate in February.
</P>
<P>
The income and spending percentages were not adjusted for
inflation. When adjusted, disposable incomes were down 0.1 percent
after rising 0.4 percent in June and spending was up 0.6 percent,
far outpacing the 0.1 percent increase a month earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
