<HEADLINE> Angola Hails UN Sanctions on Former Rebel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Prime Minister Franca
Van-Dunem, who was on his way back from Britain, said in Lisbon,
Portugal today that sanctions by U.N. Security Council on UNITA
would not threaten the peace process in Angola.
</P>
<P>
According to him, U.N. sanctions on the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) will make the former rebel
movement retrospect and carry out the Lusaka Peace Accord signed
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
He said he also believed that the sanctions would not endanger
the national unity and reconciliation government which was
founded in April this year.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council members Thursday agreed informally to
impose air and travel ban on UNITA and to close down its offices
abroad for failure to live up to the 1994 peace pact.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were endorsed by a unanimous 15-0 vote amid
fears of renewed fighting. The resolution to be adopted today
will go into force on September 30 unless U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan certifies that UNITA has taken "concrete and
irreversible steps" to fulfill its peace obligations.
</P>
<P>
Upon hearing the news of sanctions Thursday, Angolan Foreign
Minister Venancio De Moura who was visiting Cape Verde said in
Praia that the U.N. decision has reflected the wish of the
Angolan people and the international community to take on a firm
action on UNITA.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that UNITA will not mobilize its armed forces or
attempt to occupy more territories before the resolution takes
into effect on September 30. 
</P>
