<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, August 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG -- The United States has conducted about 160 air
reconnaissance missions over the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) this month, the Korean Central News Agency (KCNA)
quoted military sources as saying Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency said that on Thursday morning, an E-3
early-warning plane flew over the Korean Peninsula in coordination
with the on-going joint military exercises code-named "Ulji Focus
Lens" between the U.S. and South Korea. (DPRK-US-Reconnaissance)
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral said
Saturday that he would meet his Pakistani counterpart Nawaz
Sharif in New York next month to discuss bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
"I am going to hold talks with Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif in New York. Indo-Pakistani relations are improving. We are
hopeful that all our aspirations for improved bilateral relations
would be fulfilled," he said in West Bengal of northeastern
India. (India-Pakistan-PM Meeting)
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistan's Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan said
Saturday that Pakistan's friendship with China "is of political
and strategic importance."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Chinese correspondents here before his
forthcoming visit to China, Gohar said that Sino-Pakistani
friendship has stood the test of time in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
"Sino-Pakistani friendship based on mutual trust will remain
the cornerstone of Pakistan's foreign policy in the next 50
years," said Gohar, who is scheduled to pay a four-day visit to
China starting on Tuesday. (Pakistan-FM-China)
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- Algerian Prime Minister Ahmed Ouyahya has condemned
the massacre by terrorists in Sedi Moussa town, south of the
capital Algiers, Thursday night as "barbaric and coward act of
reprisal," the Algerian radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
An unidentified armed group perpetrated a horrible massacre
Thursday night in the small town that lies at about 20 kilometers
south of Algiers, killing 98 local people and wounding 120 others,
according to the government figures.
</P>
<P>
However, eyewitnesses put the number of deaths in this
mass-murder incident at more than 200. The massacre is the largest
terrorist act witnessed by Algeria at the hands of armed groups
over the past five years. (Algeria-Massacre)
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Shen Guofang said
here Saturday that the Chinese government highly appreciates
St. Lucia's decision on "severing diplomatic ties" with Taiwan and
establishing diplomatic relations with the People's Republic of
China (PRC).
</P>
<P>
Shen said that the establishment of diplomatic ties between
China and St. Lucia is in the fundamental interests and desire of
the two peoples, and China has decided to establish diplomatic
relations with St. Lucia on September 1 on the basis of the Five
Principles of Peaceful Co-Existence. (China-St. Lucia-Diplomatic
Ties)
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA -- Rebels of the Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) raided
a trading center in west Uganda, killing 10 and abducting other
70, local press reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The attack in early morning Friday on Kihondo trading center in
Kabarole district was confirmed by Charles Agina, the operation
commander in the district, and Davis Mudaali, the regional police
commander. (Uganda-ADF Rebels)
</P>
<P>
ABUJA -- The 20th summit of the heads of states of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) has approved a packages
of measures to accelerate sub-regional economic integration and
development.
</P>
<P>
A final communique, issued by the summit ended here Saturday
morning, noted that in the past few years, most ECOWAS countries
have made significant advance in the development of political
institutions and economic structures.
</P>
<P>
As a result of this, it said, the sub-region has recorded an
appreciable economic growth rate of about four percent, higher
than the rate of population growth. (Nigeria-ECOWAS, Integration)
</P>
