<HEADLINE> 50th Anniversary of Reclamation Drive in Heilongjiang Marked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 30 (Xinhua) -- A meeting was held today in
Harbin, the capital of northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, to
mark the 50th anniversary of the development of the province's
reclamation area.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng penned
inscriptions to mark the event.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's inscription reads: Carry forward the spirit of the
Great Northern Wilderness and continue to create new situation in
developing the cause of farmland reclamation."
</P>
<P>
Li Peng's inscription reads: "Give full play to the superiority
of the Heilongjiang Reclamation Area and accelerate construction
of a commodity grain base."
</P>
<P>
The premier also wrote a letter extending his congratulation to
the 1.6 million people living in the reclamation area.
</P>
<P>
Li expressed the hope that cadres and workers in the
reclamation area will hold high the banner of Deng Xiaoping's
theory of building socialism with Chinese characteristics, and
accelerate the industrialization of agriculture by taking
advantage of the advanced science and technology.
</P>
<P>
State Councillor Chen Junsheng made a speech at the meeting. He
noted that 50 years of development has enabled the Heilongjiang
Reclamation Area to produce a total of 200 billion kg of grain and
accumulate taxes and profits approaching six billion yuan. This,
he continued, has in turn enabled the area to vigorously supported
the country's economic construction.
</P>
<P>
The Great Northern Wilderness was developed some 50 years ago
by a group of demobilized soldiers under the direction of late
Chairman Mao Zedong and the Central Committee of the Communist
Party of China.
</P>
<P>
More than 800,000 educated young people who have joined the
reclamation effort over the past five decades have reclaimed in
total over two million ha. of wastelands and established 103
state-owned farms and increased total assets to 23.87 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Chinese vice-premiers Zou Jiahua and Jiang Chunyun also wrote
inscriptions to mark the event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
