<HEADLINE> Italy Condemns Bosnian Serb Riots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The Italian Foreign Ministry today
condemned the riots in two Bosnian towns against the NATO-led
Stabilization Force (SFOR), describing them as "unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Bosnian Serbs attacked SFOR troops with stones on
Thursday, forcing them to pull out from a police station in
Brcko. Local residents at Bijeljina also blocked SFOR troops from
taking over the police station and a television transmitter.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry said the crisis in Bosnia "must be put
down institutionally by way of elections" and elections are "a
natural way out of the crisis, a fundamental stage along the road
towards the establishment of democracy."
</P>
<P>
Tensions rose sharply over the past few days in Bosnian Serb
areas between the 3,500-strong SFOR troops and local residents
loyal to their wartime leader Radovan Karadzic as his power
struggle with Western-backed Bosnian Serb President Biljana
Plavsic was fueled up.
</P>
<P>
Those backing Plavsic and the Karadzic loyalists have been
vying for local television transmitters.
</P>
<P>
Brcko townspeople, roused from sleep by air raid sirens,
reportedly attacked dozens of American peacekeeping soldiers,
accusing the latter as behaving like the Nazi occupation force.
</P>
<P>
U.N. officials said 15 vehicles were destroyed and one American
soldier was injured. The American troops used tear gas and fired
warning shots to keep crowds away.
</P>
<P>
Bosnia Serb news media reported that at least six civilians
were injured, including five wounded by bullets that ricocheted
when an American soldier's rifle misfired.
</P>
<P>
In another development, residents in Bijeljina spent the night
on a square in front of the police station to prevent SFOR troops
from taking over the police station and a television transmitter.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 people remained there on Friday morning and planned to
stay until SFOR withdrew, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
