<HEADLINE> Pakistan, South Korea to Enhance Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and South Korea today
agreed to further promote their cooperation particularly in the
economic field.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during the talks held here today
between Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad and visiting
South Korean Vice Foreign Minister Ki-choo Lee, who arrived here
Friday on a four-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the meeting said Shamshad and Ki-choo Lee
identified various areas of economic cooperation and agreed to
increase trade between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad briefed his guest on the investment climate in
Pakistan which described as "attractive and favorable" as a result
of bold economic and fiscal revival measures introduced by the
government.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Pakistan proposed infrastructure
development, power plants, refinery projects and the textile
sector as potential fields for Korean investment.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Ki-choo Lee said that Pakistan was rich in
resources and had inexpensive manpower, friendly environment for
investment and a large market apart from its close proximity to
Central Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
He said his government would encourage South Korean investment
in Pakistan to redress the imbalance in South Korean investment in
the South Asian region.
</P>
<P>
On regional issues, Shamshad briefed Ki-choo Lee on the latest
development in the Indo-Pakistani foreign secretary-level talks
and on the latest situation in Afghanistan, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that Ki-choo Lee earlier called on Pakistani
Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan and discussed with him bilateral
relations, economic cooperation and other matters of mutual
interest.  
</P>
</TEXT>
