<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia Becomes 41st U.S. State to Sue Tobacco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Georgia became the 41st U.S.
state to sue the tobacco industry, seeking at least 8.3 billion
U.S. dollars for covering medical costs in treating
smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
The lawsuit filed Friday in Fulton County Superior Court,
accusing cigarette companies of planning and executing a public
health crisis. The state said it has incurred 2.78 billion dollars
in Medicaid costs since 1968 for treating indigent smokers.
</P>
<P>
Defendants include Philip Morris Inc., the R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco Co., Brown and Williamson Tobacco Corp., the American
Tobacco Co., the American Tobacco Council, the Council for Tobacco
Research and others.
</P>
<P>
Philip Morris executive Geoffrey Bible earlier admitted that
smoking might have caused as many as 100,000 deaths.
</P>
<P>
Forty other states have filed similar suits. Florida signed an
11.3 billion dollars settlement with the companies onday and
Mississippi settled earlier this summer for nearly 3.6 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
