<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC Chairman Meets With Swiss Guests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference CPPCC), met with here today a Swiss delegation which
just concluded a visit to Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Li expressed the hope that the delegation will give an
objective and just evaluation on Tibet and report appropriately
about the region based on their own experiences there.
</P>
<P>
To acquire a correct understanding about Tibet, it is necessary
to look at Tibet from two perspectives: the present situation and
the historical development, he said.
</P>
<P>
Due to certain natural and historical reasons, at present,
Tibet still lags behind the inland areas in economic and social
development, and faces many difficulties and problems which need
to be solved, Li said.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, since the founding of the People's Republic
of China, Tibet has scored considerable achievements in various
fields, and drastic changes have taken place there through efforts
of the Tibetan people and the support from the whole country.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, led by Ambassador Urs Ziswiler of the Swiss
foreign ministry, told Li about their deep impression on Tibet's
progress in economy, education, health, population and other
sectors, and also put forward some suggestions.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the discussion about Tibet involves a basic stand,
that is, Tibet is an inalienable part of China. Starting from this
stand, it will be easy for us to achieve common understanding either
speaking of the progress there or criticizing what you deem
necessary; starting from this stand, more shortcomings you pointed
out in our work, more helpful to us.
</P>
<P>
China has 56 nationalities, and every nationality is a member
of the Chinese nation, and there is no reason whatsoever to
discriminate against or suppress any of them, he stressed, adding
that it is an aspiration of the Tibetans as well as the central
government to speed up the development of this region. "I believe
that it is also the aspiration of the foreign friends who hope to
see that the Chinese people are leading a happy life," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the issue of religion, Li said that China upholds
the freedom of religious belief, and considers it a personal
issue, and we sincerely hope for mutual respect on this issue.
</P>
<P>
"To our mind," Li said, "religion involves broad masses of
people and nationalities and an international nature as well."
"Therefore, it is a long-term and complicated issue, and should be
handled with great prudence."
</P>
<P>
"We are atheists and there are differences between we atheists
and theists, but such differences should not mean antagonism
between people.
</P>
<P>
Under the common task of building a prosperous, democratic and
civilized modern China, differences in religious belief are the
secondary, he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Sino-Swiss relations are very good, Li said,
adding that the delegation's visit to China would help further
the friendship and cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Ziswiler said that the delegation hoped very much to learn
about Tibet. He cited a Chinese saying that "seeing is believing"
and a Swiss one that "no man is perfect", saying both sides
should therefore learn from each other and exchange their views so
as to avoid misunderstandings.
</P>
<P>
The delegation has learned much about Tibet through the visit
and has seen that Tibet has made rapid progress in many areas, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland and China have enjoyed important and good relations
and we hope that such relations would continue.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss visitors are here as guests of the CPPCC.  
</P>
</TEXT>
