<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modern Pentathlon likely to be Relegated from Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVE, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The modern pentathlon is to be
counted out of the Olympic Games, IOC president Juan was quoted as
saying in Lausanne, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Germany's Frankfurter Allgemeine
newspaper, Samaranch surprised International Olympic Committee
members here with unusually blunt comments about the future of a
sport which does not have a high number of participants around
the world.
</P>
<P>
"Modern pentathlon is going to disappear from the (Olympic)
programme," Samaranch said in the interview. Asked if he was
sure, the IOC chief added: "Very sure."
</P>
<P>
Samaranch, who was beginning a three-day meeting of the
IOC's executive board here, was not immediately available to
comment on the interview.
</P>
<P>
Modern pentathlon, which comprises swimming, shooting,
equestrian, cross-country running and fencing, has been included
in the Games since 1912 and was promoted by arguably the most
important figure in the history of the Olympics -- Baron Pierre
de Coubertin.
</P>
<P>
But it is not a popular participant sport worldwide because
of the costs involving in taking part. In recent years
organisers of the sport have tried to boost its attraction for
television by staging it over one day rather than the
traditional five.
</P>
<P>
The sport is due to be part of the next Summer Games in
Sydney in the year 2000 but its future afterwards now appears in
serious doubt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
