<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Parliament Convenes Amid Price Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi Parliament opened
its sixth session this afternoon amid renewed street protests by
main opposition parties against a recent price hike of fuel
products.
</P>
<P>
Speaker Humayun Rashid Chowdhury in his opening speech called
for cooperation of all parliament members.
</P>
<P>
"I believe amity and mutual tolerance between the treasury and
the opposition is inevitable to make this session really
meaningful and successful," he said.
</P>
<P>
Parliament sources said the session that will last for nearly a
week will have a general discussion on foreign policy and law and
order situation, and is likely to pass two new bills on local
elections.
</P>
<P>
The fuel price hike was not on the agenda of the session, but
it was apparent that the largest opposition Bangladesh Nationalist
Party (BNP) would make it a point for attacking the ruling Awami
(people's) League in the parliament, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The government earlier this month lifted the prices of all fuel
products, stirring a strong protest from the transport circle and
different political parties.
</P>
<P>
The BNP are also likely to raise issues like the
"deteriorating" economic situation, law and order, "repression" on
its activists and Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina's criticism-drawing
three-week stay in America with her daughter from late July to
early this month, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the BNP and its allies are scheduled to stage a
march tomorrow towards the parliament to press for reversal of the
fuel price hike.
</P>
<P>
The government, however, bans processions, demonstrations and
carrying of weapons in a large area around the parliament building
during the session as it does before.  
</P>
</TEXT>
