<HEADLINE> Taliban Demand Deployment of UN Monitors in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Islamic Taliban
militia today called on the United Nations to deploy monitors at
the country's airports to check arms supplies to its opponents by
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting here with the United Nations General
Secretary's special envoy on Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi, Wakil
Ahmed Motawakil who led a Taliban delegation demanded inclusion of
one representative each from Afghanistan's neighboring countries
in the UN peace team, Afghan sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Motawakil also asked the UN to shift its Special Mission for
Afghanistan from Islamabad to Kabul, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
"The mission is meant for Afghanistan and should operate in
Kabul which is now completely peaceful," the sources quoted
Motawakil as saying.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Taliban official offered to stop bombing of
civilian targets provided their rival forces do the same, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi, who is currently visiting the region as part of his
mission to assess peace prospects in Afghanistan, later left for
Tehran to discuss the Afghan situation with Iranian leaders.
</P>
