<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Host International Film Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Nineteen outstanding films from
18 countries have been selected as candidates for the "Jinjue
(Gold Wine Cup) Award", the highest award to be presented at
Shanghai International Film Festival scheduled for this fall.
</P>
<P>
The festival will also select other award-winners, including
best actor and best musical score, from amongst the 19 candidates,
which the appraisal committee selected from some 300-odd films
sent by 40 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Two Chinese films -- "Red River Valley" produced by the
Shanghai Film Studio and "Seen But Not Heard" produced by the
Pearl River Film Studio in Guangdong Province -- will compete with
overseas films for the coveted Jinjue Award.
</P>
<P>
The "Red River Valley" tells a story about the patriots of the
Tibetan and Han nationalities in their fight against British
invaders in the late 19th century.
</P>
<P>
Director Wu Yigong, chairman of the appraisal committee, noted
significant improvement in the quality of the films which have
entered this year's festival.
</P>
<P>
The 17 foreign film candidates include the Swedish film "Adam &AMP;
Eva", "L' Apartment" from France and "Cherish His Smile" from
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that more than 200 Chinese and overseas films will be
screened during the festival.
</P>
<P>
The festival will also feature a seminar on female Chinese
directors and their works will also be screened during the
festival. Eight female Chinese directors, including four from Hong
Kong and Taiwan are expected to be the topic of conversation.
</P>
</TEXT>
