<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Belgian Who Truly Sees Changes in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 30 (Xinhua) -- If the maxim "seeing is
believing" is not convincing enough to a sceptic, then someone who
saw and is still seeing has to be different.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Lerge Pairoux is a seer who, for three decades and a
half or more than half of his life, has witnessed from both inside
and outside the changes that have been taking place in China.
</P>
<P>
"The reforms and the policy of opening to the outside world has
bettered the country by leaps and bounds," said Pairoux who now
chairs the Belgium-China Cultural Center.
</P>
<P>
When talking about the changes China went through, what Pairoux
likes most is to compare the China he saw in 1962 when he first
set foot on the oriental land with the China he saw in 1997 when
he paid one of his frequent re-visits.
</P>
<P>
Venturing into China in 1960s as a French language teacher and
then as a language polisher at a Chinese press service, Pairoux
saw that the Chinese lacked material supplies needed for even
daily life and most of them were living just from hand to mouth.
</P>
<P>
He had come to know some of the whys as he spent the ensuing
six years in China until the outbreak of the Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
What made him different from other foreign visitors is the fact
that he always tried to mingle with the ordinary Chinese and get
to know their daily life.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese are best known for their hospitality. And from what
on family dining tables in the 1960s and 1990s, Pairoux has found
that life in China has really improved.
</P>
<P>
The living standards of some Chinese can even be compared with
westerners as far as luxuries are concerned, said the secretary-
general of the Belgium-China Cultural Center.
</P>
<P>
Unlike most who tend to do so, Pairoux attributed the
flourishing economy in China not simply to the reforms and opening
policy.
</P>
<P>
His insight led him to conclude that the key to China's success
started with the household contracts in the countryside and the
growth of small and medium-sized enterprises in both rural and
urban areas.
</P>
<P>
China is a large agricultural country with farmers accounting
for most of the populace, Pairoux said.
</P>
<P>
Only when life in the countryside has improved can the life in
the entire country improve for real and for good, he affirmed.
</P>
<P>
As economic development radiates to the interior from coastal
regions, the special economic zones will serve as a catalyst of
sustainable growth, said Pairoux who has witnessed as much, if not
more, development in China as that in his own homeland.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian believes that as the establishment of
high-technology industries in China churn out more jobs, the
economy will develop further. And when the economy grows, such
social problems as inadequate educational facilities and the gap
between haves and have-nots will be eventually solved.
</P>
<P>
A well-developed economy will render China its due
international prestige and confer it with its due role in the
global arena, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe it in that I saw and is still seeing it," he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
