<HEADLINE> Syrian Deputy PM Meets Iraqi Minister of Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Deputy Prime Minister
for the Economic Affairs Salim Yassin met here today with
visiting Iraqi Minister of Commerce Mohammed Mehdi Saleh, the
Syrian Arab News Agency (SANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The two officials discussed bilateral trade ties within the
context of the oil-for-food deal and potentials of expanding the
ties during the second six-month phase of the U.N.-Iraqi deal
starting as from June 9.
</P>
<P>
Saleh arrived here last Monday to take part in the 44th
Damascus International Fair which opened here Thursday. Iraq
returned to the fair after a gap of 17 years, or since the start
of an eight-year Iran-Iraq war (1980-88).
</P>
<P>
This was the first visit to Syria by a top Iraqi official
since the diplomatic ties of the two countries were severed in
1980 due to Damascus's support to Iran in the war.
</P>
<P>
The two countries began to resume economic ties in May as Iraq,
suffering a six-year-old U.N. sanctions for its invasion of
Kuwait, is seeking rapprochement with neighbors including Syria.
</P>
<P>
So far, Syria and Iraq have signed contracts worth 50 million
U.S. dollars under the oil-for-food deal which allows Iraq to
sell 2 billion dollars worth of oil under a renewed six month
period to buy food and humanitarian goods for its people.
</P>
</TEXT>
