<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Chinese City To Become Economic Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, Augest 30 (Xinhua) -- The city of Yueyang in Hunan
province, central China, which has more than 2,500-year history,
is expected to become the second largest economic and trade center
on the middle reaches of the Yangtze River, after Wuhan.
</P>
<P>
It is one of the oldest cities in central China and was known
all over Asia. In recent years, following the opening-up and
reform, its economy has been good.
</P>
<P>
According to Mayor Huang Jiaxi, Yueyang has grown into the
nation's largest concentrated feed and auto air conditioner
producer and, "We have the largest petro-chemical industrial base
and the largest paper-making mill in southern China."
</P>
<P>
Yueyang has Asia's largest ramie textile printing and dyeing
mill and boasts Southeast Asia's largest pesticides producer,
Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Yueyang is one of the eight best ports along the Yangtze, and
the second most important port, after Chongqing on the middle and
upper reaches of the river, for overseas ships to call at, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Though it was hit by series of flood last year, its GDP was
14.1 percent more than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
As of this July, there were 553 overseas-funded projects
approved by the municipal government, using 974 million US dollars
of overseas funds.
</P>
<P>
"In the next several years, more than 30 billion yuan (about
3.7 billion US dollars) of state funds will be spent on Yueyang,"
said Huang, adding that "at the end of the century, Yueyang will
hopefully be built into the second largest economic power, next
only to Wuhan on the meddle reaches of the Yangtze River."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
