<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahathir Warns of Elements Discrediting Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad today urged Malaysians to safeguard the country's
independence which he said was under the threat of being thrown
back into colonial control.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir made the remarks in a national address broadcast live
on radio and television this evening ahead of celebrations of the
country's 40th National Day tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The signs of such a likelihood were already there as could be
seen how easily foreigners could cause the collapse of the economy
by deliberately triggering a fall in the value of the Malaysian
currency and the stock market, he said.
</P>
<P>
"If we are unwilling to face this challenge with a more
patriotic attitude and hard work, we'll certainly be colonized
once more," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Don't think that once we are independent, we will be
independent forever. If we do not strive to preserve and safeguard
our independence, colonialists will return to control us directly
or indirectly," he warned.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir dwelt at length on the foreign speculative attacks and
manipulation of the currency and stock markets which he said had
chipped off 10 percent of the value of the ringgit against the
U.S. dollar in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
He urged the people to be vigilant and alert to elements in the
country that threaten to destroy what Malaysia had built and
achieved so far.
</P>
<P>
He said all the achievements could come to naught if the people
became influenced by the various claims and baseless allegations
being made and if they adopted an extreme attitude over any issue.
</P>
<P>
He said he could understand why foreigners were bent on
discrediting the country but was very disappointed when certain
Malaysians, who had benefited from the country's economic growth
made possible by the government, seemed eager to see foreigners
"blasting our economy".
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian leader said it was not easy to raise the living
standards of the people or ensuring equitable distribution of
wealth or achieving an eight percent annual economic growth since
1988 in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"Equitable distribution of wealth was not done by taking from
the rich and giving it to the poor. This was done through economic
expansion and growth," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the past four decades, he said, Malaysia has attained
successes which were never thought of when the country became
independent 40 years ago. These included building Malaysia's own
car, having its own satellite in orbit, scaling Mount Everest,
hosting the Commonwealth Games next year or having its own son
becoming president of the United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
But Mahathir admitted that Malaysia was unlikely to attain
around eight percent growth this year as projected due to the
current economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia's trade deficit was expected to increase as
more ringgit would have to be paid to finance imports due to the
fall in the currency's value while Malaysia's exports become
cheaper to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
He also called upon Malaysians to equip themselves with all
kinds of knowledge and the latest skills.
</P>
<P>
He said the 21st century would be more challenging due to the
dawn of the globalization era and sophisticated information
technology and if people stick to their present methods, Malaysia
would be left behind.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
