<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Peace, Security Keynote ECOWAS Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Wang Yongkang, Chang Yong )
</P>
<P>
ABUJA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Peace and Security still remain
the number one task ahead for west African countries to cope with
after heated discussions at a sub-regional summit which ended
here in the early hours today.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) should
have concluded its 20th summit of heads of state and government
Friday afternoon as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
However, the leaders did not return to the conference hall
until about 4:00 (3:00 GMT) this morning to make public a final
communique which contains a package of decisions on the future of
the sub-region, a product of compromise after extra hours of
heated discussions.
</P>
<P>
Like the previous ECOWAS summits since 1990 after the outbreak
of the civil war in Liberia, the authority of ECOWAS, a 16-member
economic bloc in the region, has to focus on conflict in a member
state.
</P>
<P>
This time it is the crisis in Sierra Leone, where the May 25
military coup overthrowing the legitimate government, has posed
threat on peace and security in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
It is far early to know the effect of the measures adopted by
leaders at the just-concluded summit, but the decision on Sierra
Leone has indicated that the resolution of the crisis there is
something to be accomplished at an unknown date in the future.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS leaders at the summit agreed to impose a package of
sanctions and blockade on Sierra Leone to force the military
junta in power to step down, abandoning the much asked-for
military action.
</P>
<P>
While endorsing the objective of early reinstatement of the
ousted government led by President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, the
leaders mandated the ECOWAS peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG to
monitor the ceasefire, enforce sanctions and embargo and secure
the peace in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Despite the preference by some member countries to the use of
force, the decision echoed the demand for peaceful means with the
assistance of the United Nations, the Organization of African
Unity and the entire international community which unanimously
condemned the coup and urged immediate return of democracy in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Obviously to add weight to peaceful means dealing with the
Sierra Leonean crisis, the leaders introduced Liberia, where a
new government has just emerged from a seven-year bloody civil
war, into the Committee of Four on the issue comprising Nigeria,
Ghana, Guinea and Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
The status of the committee has been upgraded from the level
of foreign ministers to that of heads of state.
</P>
<P>
The summit did not forget to call the international community
to assist the national reconstruction and resettlement of the
hundreds of thousands of refugees in Liberia to safeguard the
country's hard-earned but fragile peace, which is crucial to the
security of the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The organization announced the lift of all sanctions imposed
on Liberia during its fractional war and requested the
international community to do so. (More )

=08301300

=08301302
NNNN
20:59 21:00 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
