<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Peace, Security Keynote ECOWAS Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Wang Yongkang, Chang Yong )
</P>
<P>
ABUJA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- On the economic side, the
fundamental cause that drew the 16 countries into the
sub-regional body 22 years ago, the leaders came up at the end of
the summit without much new ideas to boost economic integration.
</P>
<P>
Collective efforts of member countries has brought about a
four percent economic growth in the sub-region over the past few
years, which is higher than that of population. Some member
countries even recorded an average 6.5-percent economic growth
rate.
</P>
<P>
But as ECOWAS Chairman, Nigeria's Head of State Sani Abacha
said at the summit that much has not been done and has to be done
particularly when the ultimate objectives, such as the creation
of a common Customs Union by the year 2000 and that of an
economic and monetary union 2005, are concerned.
</P>
<P>
The most eye-catching move the leaders decided to adopt is the
establishment of a committee made up of Cape Verde, Cote
d'Ivoire, Ghana, Mali and Togo to coordinate and monitor
sub-regional monetary integration, with an aim to adopt a single
west African currency by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The ambition of sub-regional economic integration, however, is
arduous to realize as there seems to be lack of act in unison
among member states which are yet to ratify many protocols they
signed at previous summits.
</P>
<P>
Some even refused to pay their membership dues for dozen of
years, leaving the executive secretary with a bill of arrears
exceeding 40 U.S. dollars, which, as a result, almost halted the
activity of the institution in monitoring the implementation of
the programs.
</P>
<P>
The divisive policies and other forms of alignment alleged by
Gambian Head of State Col. Yahya Jammeh, particularly the
unnecessary competition between English-speaking and
French-speaking members, also challenge the unity of ECOWAS
leaders as far as national interest is concerned.
</P>
<P>
The leaders have decided to turn the yearly summit into a
biannual event so as to provide a forum for them to give
timely touches to steer the integration process along the right
course.
</P>
<P>
It is the genuine hope of people throughout the world, and
west Africa in particular, leaders of ECOWAS states will endeavor
to strengthen unity and create an environment favorable for the
sub-region to enter the next century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
