<HEADLINE> India Envisions Economy Growth of 7-8 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Indian Finance Minister P.
Chidambaram said today that India's economy could grow at 7-8
percent annually in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
"We shall grow at 7 to 8 percent and there should also be a
mechanism to ensure that benefits of growth are shared equitably,"
the finance minister said while delivering a speech on India's
economy at the South Indian Education Society in Mumbai (Bombay).
</P>
<P>
The Indian economy must follow a road where all the 90 million
people in the country could walk with dignity, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister classified the Indian population into three groups
of 300 million each, saying that the first group has access to
fairly large income, the second group has some kind of jobs and
the third is without any kind of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
India in the past three years enjoyed an average growth in
gross domestic product of about 7 percent, as compared to a mere
3.5 percent in the first three decades after the country's
independence in 1947, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
