<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for End of US Presence in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Iranian new defense minister
today called for a Gulf countries' coordinated strategy in order
to achieve lasting security and bring an end to the presence of
the U.S. naval forces in the region.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that Minister of
Defense and Armed Forces Logistics Ali Shamkhani made the
statement in an IRNA interview here today.
</P>
<P>
Shamkhani highlighted the need to step up sincere and honest
consultations with the neighboring states, the Persian Gulf
Sheikhdoms in particular, to establish new security arrangements
to stop the presence of foreign forces in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Determining the real sources of threat in the strategic
Persian Gulf region, and whether or not the presence of foreign
forces, particularly the U.S., is itself a threat, will be among
major topics to be raised with the Persian Gulf littoral states,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Shamkhani further called for an end to the unwarranted presence
of foreign military forces in the region, U.S. forces in
particular. "Measures of this sort (ending the presence of foreign
forces) will certainly reduce regional tension," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Fifth Fleet has turned the Persian Gulf into a test
ground for its weaponry, he added.
</P>
<P>
"This, besides being a threat to the whole region, is also a
source of pollution in the Persian Gulf waters, posing a serious
threat to health, environment and economy of the entire region,"
Shamkhani noted.
</P>
<P>
On Iran's defense industries' policy, he said it focuses on
achieving self-sufficiency in conventional weapons intended for
defense of the country.
</P>
<P>
Shamkhani received the vote of confidence on August 20 from the
Parliament as the defense minister in the cabinet proposed by
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami. 
</P>
</TEXT>
