<HEADLINE> Pakistan: Ties with China, Cornerstone of Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub Khan said today that Pakistan's friendship with China
"is of political and strategic importance."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Chinese correspondents here before his
forthcoming visit to China, Gohar said that Sino-Pakistani
friendship has stood the test of time in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
"Sino-Pakistani friendship based on mutual trust will remain
the cornerstone of Pakistan's foreign policy in the next 50
years," said Gohar, who is scheduled to pay a four-day visit to
China starting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and China have enjoyed sound and mutually-beneficial
cooperation in economy, commerce, diplomatic affairs, defense and
other important fields, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This relationship in the next 50 years will be not only
between the governments but also the peoples with an access of
better understanding," he said.
</P>
<P>
Gohar, who is visiting China for the eighth time, said that the
forthcoming visit will provide him an opportunity to "renew and
strengthen the contacts" between the governments of the two
friendly countries.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Beijing, Gohar will hold talks with his
Chinese counterpart Qian Qichen on bilateral issues and regional
and international issues of mutual interest, including
Afghanistan, Kashmir and the on-going dialogue between Pakistan
and India.
</P>
<P>
He will also discuss with the Chinese foreign minister matters
relating to next year's visit by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to
Beijing, Gohar said.  
</P>
