<HEADLINE> Khan, Power Enter Hong Kong Squash Open Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Top seed and world number one
Jansher Khan of Pakistan was just one step away from winning an
eighth Hong Kong Open title after beating off a tough challenge
from Australian Brett Martin in the semi-finals of the Cathay
Pacific Squash Open here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Jansher won the semi-final match 15-11, 15-12, 9-15, 15-9 at
the 74,000 U.S. dollars event here today.
</P>
<P>
Fourth seed Canadian Jonathon Power took the other berth of the
title clash after his 15-11, 15-10, 15-6 win over second seed
Peter Nicol form Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Seven-time winner Jansher Khan from Peshwar had to resort every
ounce of his energy today to beat the 10th-ranked Australian in
the 41 minutes' match in the Hong Kong Park Indoor Games Hall.
</P>
<P>
The Peshawar prince took the number one spot for the first time
in 1987 and the top ranking has been to his credit ever since
1993.
</P>
<P>
After having two games lost to the Pakistani, Martin managed to
win one back at the third largely through the mercy of the many
errors by Jansher.
</P>
<P>
But the Pakistani did not give him more chances as he led
throughout to take the fourth and final game and the match.
</P>
<P>
The 34-year-old Australian, the winner here in 1993, blamed the
refereeing today, saying that it was hard for him to play well
when something concerning the referees came up to his mind. "They
are not experienced enough for such games. They just couldn't see
what was happening on the court," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But this happens everywhere, you know. I'm not just blaming
the refereeing here in Hong Kong," he added.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old Power, ranked fourth in the world, spent 42
minutes to win over Nicol in the other semi-final clash.
</P>
<P>
Nicol, 24, who beat Australian qualifier Byron Davis to qualify
for the semi-finals, said on Friday that the world number one spot
was in his sight.
</P>
<P>
"The number one spot is within my reach, possibly in the next
two or three months. The difference could be one tournament. If
Jansher loses in the early and I win." he said.
</P>
<P>
"I get the feeling that I can beat Jansher everytime I play
him. He's vulnerable," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nicol lost to Jansher 17-15, 9-15, 15-12, 8-15, 15-8 after two-
hour-and-six-minute battle in the final of the British Open this
April.
</P>
<P>
And Nicol avenged his April defeat by beating Jansher 3-1 at
the Al-Ahram International held in Egypt this June.
</P>
<P>
But the 22-year-old Scot might have to think twice after
today's defeat, since Jansher was not as vulnerable as he had
thought and he might have some others to beat before taking on the
king of squash from Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
