<HEADLINE> Average Family Size Reduced in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's average family size
has been reduced to four from seven in 1982 as a result of
increased access to information on family planning, the daily
''The herald'' reported today.
</P>
<P>
The drop in the size of the family has also been attributed to
growing economic hardships being faced by the country,
according
to the Zimbabwe National Family Planning Council (ZNFPC).
</P>
<P>
Shdrick Muzondo, ZNFPC information, education and
communications officer, said Friday that there had been increased
acceptance of family planning methods countrywide.
</P>
<P>
''The average family size has been going down since 1982. More
people including those in rural areas now opt for modern methods
of family planning,'' said Muzondo at an ongoing Harare
agricultural show.
</P>
<P>
ZNFPC launched a massive campaign a few years ago with the aim
to reduce the size of families. The use of condom continued to be
one of the most common methods in family planning.
</P>
<P>
A youth peer education program meant to educate the youth on
the dangers of indulging in sex is under way in rural areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
