<HEADLINE> Opinion Poll: Moi to Retain Kenyan Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 30 (Xinhua) --A recent public poll shows that
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi will retain his presidency in
the forthcoming General Election with 37.5 percent of the vote
for him.
</P>
<P>
Results of the opinion poll published by today's "Daily
Nation" indicate that Raila Odinga of the opposition National
Development Party of Kenya (NDPK) will garner 15 percent while
Mwai Kibaki of Democratic Party of Kenya (DP) and Kenneth Matiba
of Ford Asili will win 11.6 percent and 11 percent of the vote
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The poll, undertaken by a Kenyan company Strategic Public
Relations during August 9 to 15 throughout the country, shows that
the ruling Kenya African National Union will capture 67 seats in
Kenya's parliament, NDPK 22 and DP 20 of the 144 constituencies
covered by the poll.
</P>
<P>
The polling company set up last year predicts a massive
turnout with 98 percent of those polled intending to vote in the
General Elections to be held later this year.
</P>
<P>
The poll results indicate that some 62.5 percent of the voters
interviewed will vote for opposition parties which are seriously
divided.
</P>
<P>
Most of 20,000 people interviewed in the poll want a leader
who can unite Kenyans with 16.1 percent preferring a nationalist,
15.1 percent an accountable individual and 13.6 percent a
courageous and religious leader, according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
A mere 1.9 percent prefer a candidate from their own ethnic
group while only a few people would like an authoritative and
militant leader, the results show.
</P>
<P>
But officials from the polling company told a press conference
Friday that considering the majority of those interviewed
had secondary level education, the margin of error could be
higher. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
