<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Foreign Debts Increase 10 Percent: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said today that his country's foreign debts have
increased by 10 percent or more following local currency and stock
market manipulation by foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
"Their manipulation caused some 450 billion ringgit (about 160
billion U.S. dollars) to be wiped out from our capital market and
reduce our assets by 10 percent," he said when opening the 44th
general assembly of the Malaysian Chinese Association, a partner
in the ruling National Front led by the prime minister. Some 1,500
delegates attended the meeting here.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir also said Malaysia's per capita income, which had once
reached 4,600 dollars, was reduced to 4,200 dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said it was unfortunate that some foreign investors who
never set up any industries in the country but are only interested
in speculating on the stock market have turned out to be
"ungrateful".
</P>
<P>
"After reaping profits for such a long time from the country's
progress, they now try to ruin our country's economy by attacking
our currency and our stock market," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on all parties in the country to be united and join
forces in tiding over the current currency and stock market
crises.
</P>
<P>
"Let us not join in speculation activities during this
situation faced by the country. Instead, we should all help in
restoring our economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
While admitting the country's problems, the prime minister said
people should not face the problems with gloom but should regard
them as challenges and lessons to learn.
</P>
<P>
He said what had happened in the country showed that a
borderless world could prove to be a jungle full of wild beasts
and Malaysia, as a small country, could not close up its borders.
</P>
<P>
"We will develop the skills to live in this jungle and will
develop the skills to handle the wild beasts which roam inside
it," he said.
</P>
<P>
"What is important is that in efforts to overcome the country's
economic problems, we should continue to have political
stability," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He urged the National Front component parties to ensure that
they are strong and stable and continue to support the coalition's
concept of consultation and consensus.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
