<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange (KLSE) was under much foreign selling pressure this week
pushing all the indexes down by a big margin.
</P>
<P>
The Composite Index closed the week at 804.40 points, down by
100.60 points from 905.00 points at last week's close, the EMAS
Index dropped 40.30 points to 219.48, the Second Board Index
dropped sharply by 111.51 points to 373.74 while the Industrial
Index slipped 259.33 points to 1,619.23.
</P>
<P>
The week saw the Composite Index touched a 31-month low at
856.00 points on Tuesday before hitting 812.18 points on Thursday,
a new four-year low, on continued foreign selling following the
delivery before sale ruling.
</P>
<P>
The mainboard volume increased to 1.585 billion shares worth
6.201 billion ringgit (about 2.21 billion U.S. dollars) from 1.047
billion shares valued 4.934 billion ringgit (about 1.76 billion
U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover also rose to 197.236 million shares
worth 1.575 billion ringgit (about 560 million U.S. dollars) from
144.585 million shares valued at 1.489 billion riinggit (about 530
million U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Off market deals increased to 199.441 million shares worth
1.315 billion ringgit (about 469 million U.S. dollars) from
138.584 million shares worth 1.301 billion ringgit (about 464
million U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Two counters made their debut this week -- Padi Beras Nasional
(Bernas) at an issue price of 2.20 ringgit on Monday and RHB
Sakura Merchant Bankers Bhd at 4.10 on Tuesday with Bernas ending
the week unchanged at 1.97 ringgit and RHB Sakura gaining 14 sen
to 3.42 ringgit.
</P>
<P>
The 10 most active counters were Renong, down 26 sen to 3.00
ringgit with a volume of 174.901 million shares, Suria Capital,
dipping 43 sen to 1.88 ringigt with 53.413 million shares traded,
Rekapacific losing 80 sen to 1.39 ringgit with 44.876 million
shares traded, MBf Capital dropping 64 sen to 2.74 ringgit with
42.414 million shares traded, Magnum falling 55 sen to 2.71
ringgit (38.374 million shares), MPHB dropping 83 sen to 2.27
ringgit with 33.130 million shares traded, Sime Darby falling
1.05 ringgit to 6.90 ringgit (32.164 million shares), Sriwani
slipping 72 sen to 3.62 ringgit (31.558 million shares), Pelangi
down three sen to 2.79 ringgit (29.694 million shares) and MRCB
dropping 1.59 ringgit to 2.35 ringgit (29.522 million shares).
</P>
<P>
Consumer products accounted for 96.534 million shares traded,
industrial products 150.090 million shares traded, construction
245.702 million shares, trading/services 408.654 million shares,
infrastructure 11.814 million shares, finance 304.108 million
shares, hotels 13.839 million shares, properties 213.892 million
shares, plantation 37.586 million shares, mining 8.124 million
shares, trusts 2.072 million shares, closed/fund 1.189 million
shares and loan stocks 98.303 million shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
