<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy on Afghanistan Leaves for Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 30 (Xinhua) -- United Nations (U.N.)
Secretary-General's Special Envoy Lakhdar Brahimi left here today
for Tehran, capital of Iran, to hold talks with Iranian leaders on
Afghanistan's situation.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day visit to Tehran, Brahimi, who is on a
two-week mission to assess the Afghan situation and the U.N. peace
efforts in the war-torn country, will meet Iranian new Foreign
Minister Kamal Kharazi, U.N. sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi's visit to Iran is part of his mission to consult
relevant countries on the Afghan issue.
</P>
<P>
The 63-year-old envoy will submit his report on Afghanistan to
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan before the U.N. General Assembly
session starts in New York next month.
</P>
<P>
After his trip to Iran, the former Algerian foreign minister
will proceed to Moscow and then in the last leg of his tour he
will meet Saudi Arabian officials before returning to Pakistan,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Since his arrival in the region in mid-August, Brahimi has held
talks with Pakistani leaders on the Afghan issue and met leaders
of the Afghan Taliban militia and the rival northern alliance.
Brahimi has also visited Tajikistan, Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
