<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin, Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of the
crude palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week all
higher.
</P>
<P>
On the CPO cash market, the week saw steady trading for the
first four days and a slight drop in demand last trading day.
</P>
<P>
August South soared by 55 ringgit (about 19 U.S. dollars) to
1,350 ringgit (about 482 U.S. dollars) per ton in comparison with
the price at last week's close.
</P>
<P>
Players are hoping for prices to stay on the uptrend next week
as sentiment in the market is still bullish with the influx of
overseas buyers.
</P>
<P>
Tin was traded on the Kuala Lumpur tin Market (KLTM)
substantially higher above the 15.00 ringgit (about 5.3 U.S.
dollars) per kg level this week.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit's relative weakness boosted demand for local tin
throughout the week, anaylsts said, adding that however, the
performance of ringgit against the U.S dollar would continue to
dictate the movements of KLTM.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit dropped to its lowest level of 2.9640/90 on Friday
morning before settling at 2.8949/95 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The KLTM's accumulated turnover broadened to 796 tons against
568 tons last week.
</P>
<P>
In comparison with three-month tin on the London Metal
Exchange, the local tin recorded a discount between 10 U.S.
dollars per ton and 95 U.S. dollars per ton except on Monday
which saw a premium of 20 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Over the trading week, the Malaysian rubber market was steadier
with prices quoted at a very supportive levels.
</P>
<P>
Against last week's close, September RSS-One jumped nine sen to
259.00 sen (92.5 U.S. cents) per kg while SMR 20 was 7.50 sen
higher to 256.00 sen (about 91.4 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization's (INRO) daily
market indicator price for August 28 was at 195.57
Malaysia/Singapore cents per kg against 191.03 cents on August 21.
</P>
<P>
The five-day moving average stood at 193.93 cents per kg
compared with 191.76 cents last week.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian rubber market is seen continuing its pick up next
week with the RSS grade poised to hit the 265.00 sen mark, taking
advantage of the weaker ringgit, analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
