<HEADLINE> Sudanese Rebel Leader Vows to Continue War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The visiting Sudanese
People's Liberation Army leader Johan Garang has vowed to go on
fighting against the central government.
</P>
<P>
"We are preparing ourselves to defend our gains as well as to
extend them," local daily, The Citizen, quoted Garang as saying
today.
</P>
<P>
Garang met Thursday South African President Nelson Mandela,
who was facilitating a peace talks between the Sudanese
government and rebels in a bid to end the 14-year civil war in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese rebels have been fighting to get greater autonomy
or independence from the north.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on departure for home yesterday, Garang
said: "We want a new Sudanese political dispensation... based on
our realities, on the diversity that we have." Sudan is a
multi-racial, multi-ethnic, multi-cultural, multi-religious
community.
</P>
<P>
"The unity of the country must be based on these realities.
Otherwise... we should have a friendly, amicable and peaceful
divorce," Garang said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he will not talk to the Sudanese government
leader Omar El-Bashir except on the basis of 1994 peace
principle.
</P>
<P>
Garang said that he had urged Mandela "to appeal to Bashir to
take the peace process seriously". 
</P>
