<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestinians Welcome Albright's Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Both Israel and Palestinians
have expressed welcome to the announcement that U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright will begin a week-long Middle East trip
from September 9, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the trip in Washington, U.S. State Department
spokesman James Ruben said that the peace process in Middle East
is in trouble and the secretary plans to remain in the region for
at least a week.
</P>
<P>
Albright Friday telephoned Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian President Yasser Arafat to inform them
of her upcoming visit to the region.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's spokesman Shai Bazak said the prime minister has
expressed welcome to the secretary's planned visit. He said
Israel and the United States shared the view that the Palestinian
National Authority (PAN) is not doing enough to crack down on
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu told Albright that the security situation
had improved sufficiently for Israel to ease its closure on the
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, on the Palestinian side, Saeb Erakat, the PNA's
senior negotiator, also welcomed Albright's visit.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting of the Palestinian cabinet in
Bethlehem, West Bank, he stressed that Albright should
concentrate on persuading Israel to stop construction of
settlements in the West Bank, confiscation of land and
demolition of homes.
</P>
<P>
It will be Albright's first visit to the region after her
seven months in office, which will take her to Israel, Egypt,
Jordan, Syria and Saudi Arabia. She will also meet with Arafat in
the Palestinian controlled areas and may go to Lebanon as well.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Israeli opposition Labor party leader Ehud Barak
said that the secretary's visit should be used to renew an
initiative to withdraw Israeli troops from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Israel Television Friday night, Barak proposed
that Albright go to Damascus with a new plan for a staged,
supervised and slow withdrawal from Lebanon that will include
Syrian guarantees and the entry of the Lebanese army and
international force. Barak said the whole process could be
accomplished in a matter of month.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu said that the Israeli government's policy on
Lebanon has not changed. He said that "if we depart from
Lebanon, Lebanese will come to us and reach the Galilee
border." He added that it is far from finding a stable solution
in Lebanon that will enable Israel to leave.
</P>
<P>
Israel has occupied an area of 1,000 square kilometers of the
Lebanon territories, which it self-styled as "security zone."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
