<HEADLINE> Commerce Contributes More to GDP Growth in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 30 (Xinhua) -- With an adequate supply and
stable price, the commerce sector is contributing more to the GDP
growth in Shanghai, China's largest commercial center.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the commerce sector generated 20.5 billion
yuan (2.498 billion US dollars) to Shanghai's GDP in the first
seven months, a year-on-year increase of 14.5 percent. The figure
represented 11.28 percent of the city's GDP, and 25.11 percent of
the gross output value of the tertiary or service industry.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, GDP in the commercial sector amounted to 31.584
billion yuan, making up 10.98 percent of the city's GDP and 26.03
percent of the output value of the tertiary industry.
</P>
<P>
Rapid growth has been reported in Shanghai's commercial sector
over recent years. By 1996, the sector had boasted more than
196,000 retail and wholesale outlets that have employed some 1.45
million people.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the chain-store business, which generated 4.5 billion
yuan in turnover in 1996, is also accountable substantially to the
growth.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also suggest that the sales income of foodstuffs has
been on the decline while that of garments and other daily-use
items has been on the rise, indicating the rising standards of
people's livelihood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0140 </DOCNO>
