<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Takes Measures Against Cattle Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe is taking preventiveve
measures against a cattle disease which is threatening to wipe
out cattle of one of its neighbors, a local daily " The Herald''
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted Stuart Hargreaves, Director of the Veterinary
Services, as warning that although the cattle in Zimbabwe is safe
at the present from the deadly lung disease, the chances of the
disease occurring could not be ruled out.
</P>
<P>
"There are always risks and we need to protect our borders. We
have to be vigilant and carry out continued surveillance, so that
the disease does not come into the country,'' said Hargreaves.
</P>
<P>
He said that his department is in the process of training its
personnel on how to deal with the disease.
</P>
<P>
A cattle disease named Bovine Pluro Pneumonia, a lung disease,
now is threatening to wipe out the cattle in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The disease was first reported in Botswana where it has
claimed over 360,000 beasts and is reported to have spread to
Angola, then Zambia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
