<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Approves Plan for Faster Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The 20th summit of the heads of
states of the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS)
has approved a packages of measures to accelerate sub-regional
economic integration and development.
</P>
<P>
A final communique, issued by the summit ended here this
morning, noted that in the past few years, most ECOWAS countries
have made significant advance in the development of political
institutions and economic structures.
</P>
<P>
As a result of this, it said, the sub-region has recorded an
appreciable economic growth rate of about four percent, higher
than the rate of population growth.
</P>
<P>
The communique emphasized the need for the member countries to
implement sound macro-economic policies so as to consolidate
their success in inflation control, monetary discipline and
improved adjustment policies.
</P>
<P>
It commended the move by the international community to
resolve the debt problems of heavily indebted poor countries, but
regretted that only two ECOWAS countries has been qualified to
benefit from the program.
</P>
<P>
Noting that significant development can only be achieved
through good long-term development strategies, the summit urged
member countries to develop their long-term development plans,
such as the African Elephant Program of Cote d'Ivoire and the
Vision 2010 of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS leaders also re-affirmed their full commitment to
regional monetary integration and the eventual adoption of a
single West African currency.
</P>
<P>
To realize this goal by the year 2000, the summit approved a
committee comprising the heads of state of Cape Verde, Cote
d'Ivoire, Ghana, Mali and Togo to co-ordinate and monitor the
program.
</P>
<P>
The summit decided that an ECOWAS travel cheque will be
launched by the end of the year to make trade within the
community easier.
</P>
<P>
To solve the serious financial difficulties facing ECOWAS
institutions, the summit passed a resolution urging all member
countries to immediately ratify the protocol for the application
of a community level fees that will replace the current member
contributions.
</P>
<P>
In view of the success of the first phase of the ECOWAS
sub-regional telecommunications network, the summit approved the
second phase of program to be known as INTELCOM II.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, the program will lead to the
modernization and expansion of telecommunications in the
sub-region through full digitalization and the use of other
modern facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
