<HEADLINE> NBA Hoop Stars Arrives in Beijing in Asian Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Two star players of the National
Basketball Association arrived here on Saturday on the final leg
of their week-long Asian tour.
</P>
<P>
David Robinson of San Antonio Spurs and Joe Smith of Golden
State Warriors, spent the earlier part of the week in Chinese
Taipei and Hong Kong, China, conducting skills clinics with local
high school players as part of NIKE's ongoing initiative to give
more kids in Asia access to top-level basketball.
</P>
<P>
Their Beijing visit is special for Joe and David, as they
opened a completely refurbished basketball court and played a
little friendly three-on-three with some local Chinese youths.
</P>
<P>
"I'm proud to be part of this dedication today", said
Robinson. "This court is just one way the NIKE, the community and
athletes like myself can participate in the lives of kids in
China."
</P>
<P>
Additionally, the NBA superstars also got a chance to check out
the local competition, joint coaching session with China's leading
center Wang Zhizhi of the August First Rockets, and a group of top
high school players.
</P>
<P>
"It's important to have a dream," Wang, the China's hoops hero,
said to the 120 kids assembled at the court. "Whether your dream
is to play professionally or not, work hard, play sports for the
enjoyment of it and just be confident in yourself."
</P>
<P>
The NBA Asian tour is part of an ongoing commitment of NIKE to
build participation in basketball and upgrade skills in China and
across the Asian region.
</P>
<P>
Besides Robinson and Smith, past visitors to the region include
Alonzo Mourning and Penny Hardaway, who visited China in 1994,
Jason Kidd, Damon Stoudamire, Michael Finley, Michael Jordan and
Charles Barkely. 
