<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Morocco Makes Progress in Talks on West Sahara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON August 29 (Xinhua) -- The Moroccan government and the
Popular Front of the Liberation of West Sahara reached a
compromise agreement here today on deployment of troops in West
Sahara, repatriation of refugees and release of political
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
During the fourth round of direct talks between representatives
of both sides which ended a day earlier, one issue that remains to
be resolved is to reach agreement on the detailed code of a
referendum on West Sahara's future.
</P>
<P>
The talks were chaired by U.N. special envoy for West Sahara
James Baker, former U.S. Secretary of State, who described the
talks as "fruitful".
</P>
<P>
Baker said that the next round of talks are expected to take
place in the United States on September 12-14, which will focus on
the behavior of both sides in the referendum.
</P>
<P>
He said the talks are of great significance which would be the
last effort made by the U.N. special mission for the referendum in
West Sahara before its term expires on September 30, hoping that
the two sides would close their differences and find a final
solution to the issue.
</P>
<P>
The original plan for a referendum on the future of West Sahara
in January 1992 has been postponed because Morocco and the Popular
Front could not reach an agreement on the list of voters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
