<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's External Debt Stands at 7,845.7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's total external
debt committed as at July 31, is 7,845.7 million US dollars, out of
which the disbursed outstanding debt is 6,440.7 million dollars or
82.1 percent, while the committed undisbursed debt is 1,405 million
dollars or 17.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed in the latest monthly economic review of the
Bank of Tanzania (BOT) available here today.
</P>
<P>
The profile of disbursed outstanding debt by creditor category
revealed that bilateral and multilateral debts accounted for 45.7
percent and 47.2 percent of the total debt respectively.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of the debt owed to commercial sources was very
small accounting for 3.6 percent and 3.5 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The structure of disbursed outstanding debt by borrower category
showed that the central government was the largest borrower,
accounting for as much as 94.1 percent, while that of the private
sector in the total debt was 3.0 percent, the BOT report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Awareness Increases in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 30 (Xinhua) -- In Tanzania, 82 percent of
women and 91 percent of men have changed their sexual behavior to
avoid getting AIDS, according to the report of a latest demographic
and health survey conducted in the country.
</P>
<P>
The majority of those who reported to have changed their sexual
behavior said they restricted themselves to one sexual partner.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 39 percent of women and 55 percent of men
regard the use of condoms as a way to avoid AIDS, while
one-fourth say having only one partner can help prevent the
spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said, testing for HIV/AIDS is still very low
in the country as only four percent of women and 11 percent of men
said that they had tested for their sero-status, two thirds of them
expressed desire to be tested.
</P>
<P>
The majority of people are also aware of other sexually transmitted
diseases, according to the survey.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
