<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Bank Turns Employees Into Contract Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai branch of China's
largest bank, the Industrial and Commercial Bank of China (ICBC),
will transform its 15,000 employees into contract workers in three
months in a bid to boost efficiency.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,000 employees in three sub-branches of ICBC
Shanghai have already signed labor contracts, signifying an
official start of personnel reform in the banking sector, which
has long been renowned for the availability of a "golden rice
bowl" -- permanent employment.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Jianqing, president of ICBC Shanghai, said that the
personnel system under a planned regime has greatly discounted the
enthusiasm and creativity of both the executives and employees and
therefore impeded the growth of banking business.
</P>
<P>
The contract system, first piloted on a trial basis in the
Pudong branch in 1993, will spread to nearly 30 subsidiaries and
over 600 business operations in several phases, covering more than
15,000 employees in aggregate, he said.
</P>
<P>
The reform plan has met with an enthusiastic response from the
employees, Jiang noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> St. Lucia Severs Diplomatic Ties with Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The Prime Minister of
Saint Lucia, Kenny Anthony, announced tonight that his Labour
Party government has decided to establish full diplomatic
relations with the People's Republic of China and sever so-called
diplomatic ties with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
In a nationwide-televised and broadcast address, Anthony
stressed that his government's decision "is in keeping with
international developments on the non-recognition of Taiwan as a
legitimate state."
</P>
<P>
"The majority of countries in the world today have full
diplomatic relations with the People's Republic of China," he
said, adding that "from the point of view of international law,
the recognition of the administration on Taiwan as the government
of all China, is not tenable," he added.
</P>
<P>
"By concluding diplomatic relations with the People's Republic
of China, Saint Lucia will only be modernising its foreign policy,
and proceeding in a direction which the majority of the world's
states have already trod," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the Ministry of Foreign and International
Trade of Saint Lucia announced in a press release that it "has
informed" Taiwan that the government of Saint Lucia "will be
establishing full diplomatic relations with the People"s Republic
of China as of Monday 1st September 1997."
</P>
<P>
Saint Lucia, an island in the Caribbean Sea, is the second
largest of the Windward Islands of the Lesser Antilles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
