<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ricupero: UNCTAD, China Enjoy Close Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 29 (Xinhua) -- UNCTAD Secretary-General Rubens
Ricupero said he is satisfied with the close cooperative
relationship between UNCTAD and China, hoping that the latter can
do more for the development of other developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"China has been a strong supporter of UNCTAD and contributed
significantly to its work," Ricupero, the head of the United
Nations Conference on Trade and Development, said. "It has
participated actively in UNCTAD inter-governmental
deliberations. It is one of the few developing countries that have
made financial contributions to UNCTAD on an annual basis."
</P>
<P>
UNCTAD has also made useful contributions, through its policy
analysis and technical cooperation, in the process of China's
policy formulation and implementation, particularly in the area of
trade and investment, Ricupero said in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The UNCTAD Trade and Development Reports have been translated
into Chinese. They have been used as training material for senior
officials and as the important source of reference on investment
in many official documents.
</P>
<P>
Ricupero hopes that China can play a more active role in
</P>
<P>
-- Developing a positive agenda for the developing countries in
the multilateral negotiations;
</P>
<P>
-- Strengthening further South-South cooperation, promoting
trade and investment to and from other developing countries;
</P>
<P>
-- Promoting the development of the least-developed countries.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of China's accession to the World Trade
Organization (WTO), Ricupero shares the argument that China
needs WTO and WTO needs China. Ricupero has been chairman of
General Council of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
(GATT), WTO's predecessor, chairman of the Contracting Parties,
and chairman of the developing countries in the GATT.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that China has made some impressive progress,"
Ricupero said. "I hope that in the coming months some important
political events that are going to take place, like the summit
between China and the United States, could add an important
political element to China's accession to WTO." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
