<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Investors Allowed to Set Up Private Business in Fujian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong residents are allowed
to set up overseas-funded firms or individually-owned, private
businesses in east China's Fujian Province, according to new
government policy.
</P>
<P>
Under the policy of the Fujian provincial government, the
private businesses to be run in Fujian by residents of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) will enjoy the same
preferential treatment as local residents in term of trade
operation and way of management.
</P>
<P>
While the duration of operation is decided by the relevant
government stipulations, the duration of the business license for
the Hong Kong firms will be determined by the period of validity
of the proprietors' "temporary residence cards" and, in case of
need, applications can be raised for extension of their residence
and businesses.
</P>
<P>
To allow Hongkong residents to run private business in Fujian
is a new move initiated by the provincial government to expand
Fujian-Hong Kong economic and trade cooperation, which went into
trial operation on July 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rupiah Crashes to Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah Friday
plummeted to an all-time low of 3,070 against the U.S. dollar from
the 2,970 close Thursday after the central bank reportedly tried
to inject liquidity and cut interest rates, dealers said today.
</P>
<P>
Spot rupiah, which opened at 3,020/3,040, touched an historic
low of 3,070 in early trading but bounced back in the afternoon to
close at 2,890/2,910.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the drop in the rupiah value was caused by
reports that the government will soon remove the tight monetary
policy which set a high interest rate and the central bank had
injected liquidity in some small and medium banks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Jakarta Stock Exchange suffered another large
intraday loss Friday amid uncertainty over the rupiah's direction
and regional market slump.
</P>
<P>
Stockbrokers said share prices fell 6.9 percent, pushing the
composite index down to a 21-month low or its worst one-day loss
in eight years.
</P>
<P>
The composite index lost 36.404 points to close at 493.962,
with turnover totaling 425.85 million shares worth 260.9 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Securities analysts and brokers said Friday's steep fall in the
stock market was not expected by most investors.
</P>
<P>
"The market has already collapsed, no one can save it now but
the government," said an analyst.
</P>
<P>
A senior stockbroker with a joint venture securities firm said
Friday's breaking of 500-point psychological index level would
further dampen the market.
</P>
<P>
Bankers warned on Friday that a prolonged tight monetary policy
could lead to bank defaults and corporate bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
Some cabinet ministers have also expressed similar concerns,
saying that a tight monetary policy was dampening the investment
climate in the country. It should not be maintained too long as it
would kill small and medium businesses, they added.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said the government will soon hold a meeting
to be attended by all cabinet ministers to discuss the rupiah
crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
