<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico's Elderly Population Growing Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's population is going
through an accelerated "aging" process, with people 60 years of
age or more making up six percent of the country's population, the
National Population Council (NPC) announced today.
</P>
<P>
That segment of the population, which is called the Third Age
people, will grow to 76 percent in the next 15 years and account
for 22 percent of the country's total population, said NPC.
</P>
<P>
The source attributed the change in the age group to the
increase in life expectancy. The change also presents challenges
to government in order to ensure the Third Age people with a
comfortable life.
</P>
<P>
The main challenges include the improvement of health services,
pensions, entertainment, recreation and retirement funds, said
NPC.
</P>
<P>
The sustained reduction in the mortality rate since the 1930s
has given rise to a significant increase in the average life
expectancy of Mexicans, according to NPC.
</P>
<P>
The World Day of the Elderly was commemorated here Thursday. It
is a celebration initiated by the United Nations in 1978. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
