<HEADLINE> Pakistan-India Talks Likely to Be Delayed: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The third round of foreign
secretary-level talks between Pakistan and India, scheduled to
take place in New Delhi next month, is likely to be postponed
until the end of October, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We are almost certain that India is creating hurdles in so
many ways to put off the talks, the dates of which were not
decided," the News quoted a senior Pakistani official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report said that an important reason was that India wants
to see the outcome of visits by the prime ministers of Pakistan
and India to New York.
</P>
<P>
Both prime ministers are supposed to meet U.S. President Bill
Clinton, separately, as they go to New York for the U.N. General
Assembly meetings on September 22, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India resumed their foreign secretary-level talks
in March after a hiatus of three years, amid signs of improved
relations between the two arch rivals in South Asia. The talks
broke down in January 1994 due to their differences over the issue
of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local newspapers today reported that the Clinton
administration had conceded Indian demand to restrict the talks
between Clinton and Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral
mainly to bilateral ties and to keep hands off India-Pakistan
dialogue.  
</P>
