<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Law of Bank Approved in Poland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The Polish legislature approved
today the Law of Bank which is intended to strengthen laws against
economic crimes and enhance supervision over banks.
</P>
<P>
The law will help provide more thorough investigations into
economic crimes by requiring banks to provide information
concerning secret material to the courts and the procurator's
office when accusations or charges are lodged against banks or
accounts.
</P>
<P>
Currently, such secret material is provided only when a lawsuit
is initiated.
</P>
<P>
The law also establishes a system of registration in order to
prevent money laundering.
</P>
<P>
The applicants who wish to run a bank must prove the legality
of the source of their capital.
</P>
<P>
The one who owns cash deposits exceeding a certain sum must be
registered.
</P>
<P>
The sum of stock shares which a bank purchases must not surpass
15 percent of the bank's own capital.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, the appointment of the president of a bank will
be subject to the approval of the president of the national bank,
who can only recommend candidates for bank presidency at present.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0178 </DOCNO>
