<HEADLINE> Cambodian Refugees to be Sent Home Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Around 27,000 Cambodian refugees
will be sent back home from northeastern Thailand's province of
Surin during the next two weeks, Thai Army Commander-in-Chief Gen.
Chetta Thanajaro has said, according to local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
During a tour of the Thai-Cambodian border in Surin province on
Friday, Chetta said repatriations must be conducted on a voluntary
basis and be viewed by the press.
</P>
<P>
He said refugees being housed in Surin province were facing
water shortages and about 7,000 people were suffering from
malaria, cold and intestinal diseases. Seven people had died so
far, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chetta said Cambodian Second Prime Minister Hun Sen's forces
had seized most of the Cambodian border town of O'Smach, the last
stronghold of those loyal to Prince Norodom Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
He said Cambodia's co-defense minister Gen. Tea Banh told him
that Phnom Penh was ready to welcome all Cambodian people back.
