<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ricupero: China to Play Big Role in Shaping 21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 29 (Xinhua) -- UNCTAD Secretary-General Rubens
Ricupero said he believes what is happening now in China is the
most significant, historical change in the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
"The changes in China are the events that will have more impact
in shaping the next century," Ricupero, head of the United Nations
Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD), told Xinhua in an
exclusive interview on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the importance of those achievements is the
successful, cautious and gradual way in which the Chinese
leadership and the Chinese people have made during the transition
to a market economy. I believe the success of the Chinese
experiment is one of the brightest hopes for the next century."
</P>
<P>
In contrast to many others' experiences of the so-called "shock
therapy," the UNCTAD chief said, China has chosen a very secure
road, trying step by step, and the results have confirmed the
wisdom of this choice.
</P>
<P>
China registered an annual GDP growth of about 12 percent for
the last five consecutive years. The economy was handled
cautiously, and a "soft-landing" was achieved. Inflation has also
been brought down to 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
"What is impressive is that it was achieved at the same time
China opened its economy, its door to foreign trade, foreign
competition, and foreign investment," Ricupero stressed.
</P>
<P>
Ricupero, who visited China last December, said he was
impressed by China's success in eliminating poverty, while making
great achievements in economic development.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the fact that the number of rural poor in China
fell from 94 million to 65 million between 1991 and 1995, Ricupero
said: "This is amazing because it is unique to have a country with
1.2 billion people who are now practically, with all the basic
needs satisfied in terms of the levels of subsistence of food,
clothes, education, health, etc. "
</P>
<P>
he said China's most important achievement is the success in
eliminating poverty because that should be the goal of any country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ricupero: China to Play Big Role in Shaping 21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ricupero underlined that there are two major achievements in
the external aspects of China's economic development. The first is
the big success of China as the largest recipient of foreign
direct investment (FDI) among developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Now China is receiving almost 50 percent of the FDI among
developing countries. In terms of countries in general, for the
last four consecutive years, China has been the second largest,
immediately after the United States, attracting 42 billion U.S.
dollars in 1996. In terms of portfolio equity funds, China is also
the largest recipient among developing countries. The total net
assets of China investment funds alone reached 6.68 billion
dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The second, Ricupero said, is the enormous change in the growth
of China's foreign trade. During the 1991-1995 period, China's
annual average trade growth was 19.5 percent, as compared to 7
percent of the world average.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the ranking of China in the world trade went from
15th place in 1992 to 11th in 1996. That was an enormous rise and
the rise was not only in exports, but also in imports. While the
economy of the industrialized countries was in recession or in
slow growth in recent years, China was one of the main sources of
import demand for industrialized economies, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ricupero said he was optimistic about China's future. "The
world in general, the developing countries in particular, need a
rich and prosperous China. It is not only because China represents
a large share of mankind, but also because of the rich cultural
heritage, and the potential that China may represent in terms of
import demand," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"We see the success of the Chinese experiment as a success of
developing countries in general because we are sure that we will
always find in China the right attitude to development. China has
faced the same problems as most of the poor countries and China
remains committed to the course of development," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ricupero does not agree with the Western press's claim that
China's growth in economy is a menace or a threat. He said people
who are afraid of imports from China should be aware that Chinese
growth is two-way: it adds to the world and as Chinese become more
and more able to consume goods, china will become more and more
the largest market in the world.
</P>
<P>
The UNCTAD secretary-general said the reform of state-owned
enterprises is a major challenge that policy-makers in China are
facing. He does not think that radical initiatives should be
considered a good policy option. A number of Chinese state-owned
enterprises have proved to be able to compete effectively in
domestic and international markets, Ricupero noted.
</P>
<P>
He hoped China would continue efforts to minimize the imbalance
between coastal regions and interior. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
