<HEADLINE> Hungary to Hold Referendum on NATO Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The Hungarian government is
planning to hold a referendum to decide whether the country should
join the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), the local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The referendum is scheduled for November 16 this year, the
government announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hungarians hold differing views and opinions on whether or not
their country should join NATO. Last July, NATO invited Hungary,
Poland, and the Czech Republic to join NATO in the first wave
during its Madrid summit.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Gyula Horn told reporters that the purpose of
his decision is to create a stable situation in the country. Horn
expressed confidence that the majority of the residents would vote
in favor of NATO membership for Hungary.
</P>
<P>
The referendum will also ask voters to decide on whether land
can be sold to foreigners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
