<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prison Administration Official on Truth about Tibetan Prisons (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- A prison administration official
in Tibet refuted US Representative Frank Wolf today, citing Wolf's
report on the prison situation in Tibet as a "fabrication."
</P>
<P>
Wolf sneaked into Tibet using false ID in flagrant violation of
Chinese law and smeared the prison administration in Tibet with
his hearsay, according to Tsering Puncog, director of the Bureau
of Prison Administration of the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
He said that Tibet will open its prisons to those who really
want to know the situation there. In the past six months, the
bureau has made arrangements for officials from four countries to
visit prisons.
</P>
<P>
"The conclusion they've drawn from what they've witnessed is
contrary to what Wolf described in his report, which is based on
rumors," Tsering Puncog said.
</P>
<P>
Tibet now has three prisons, and the number of prisoners is
only 0.075 percent of the autonomous region's population, he said,
adding that prisoners charged with endangering state security
account for nine percent of that number, the rest have committed
criminal offences.
</P>
<P>
"If Wolf had seen the prisons with his own eyes, and if he were
not prejudiced and honest, he would have found that our jails
treat and reform prisoners with a spirit of socialist
humanitarianism," he said.
</P>
<P>
Prison authorities treat every convict equally and respect
their rights. On no account will the convicts be discriminated
against or mistreated, no matter what they were charged with.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prison Administration Official on Truth about Tibetan Prisons (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prisoners have days off on weekends, national holidays, and
Tibetan festivals. And their ethnic lifestyle and customs are well
respected and the administration tries to prepare special food for
them.
</P>
<P>
The cells are warm and tidy, and equipped with good ventilation
and electric lighting, according to Puncog.
</P>
<P>
Each prisoners has a monthly allocation of 20 kg of food grain,
2.5 kg of meat, and 15 kg of vegetables, plus some tea and
non-staple foodstuff like butter.
</P>
<P>
"With part of the money from their labor, prisoners here
actually have yearly living expenses averaging 2,500 yuan (some
300 US dollars) per person, 300 yuan more than the state
standards," said Puncog, and a food management committee formed by
prisoners ensures that they get hot, clean food with adequate
nutrition.
</P>
<P>
There is a clinic in each jail providing adequate medical
treatment and regular check-ups. In case of serious illness that
the clinic can not handle, the patient is sent to a nearby local
hospital and the medical bill would is paid by the prison.
</P>
<P>
If the patient needs long-term medical care, he can get
assistance from family members or financial aid from the prison if
he runs into financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Tsering Puncog expressed his indignation at Wolf's accusations
about inmates being beaten up in prison.
</P>
<P>
To protect prisoners' dignity, the prison administration
prohibits the use of abusive language or the beating up of
prisoners. And they are not allowed to use manual labor to punish
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
This is all under the local people's procuratorate, people's
congress, and the people's political consultative conference
supervision, Puncog noted.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the prisoners have the right to report, accuse, or
even bring a lawsuit against prison guards if they are ill-treated
and their accusations should not be suppressed, he said. And the
local procuratorate has placed a special box in each jail for
prisoners' report or accusation letters, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prison Administration Official on Truth about tibetan Prisons (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since prisoners usually do not have much education, prison
authorities provide education programs to teach them how to read
and write in the Tibetan language. Each prisoner can choose
classes that suit their educational background.
</P>
<P>
Some 70 people have obtained certificates by taking part in
examinations by various schools.
</P>
<P>
Tsering Puncog noted that prisoners can get books and
newspapers, listen to radio, and watch TV. They are encouraged to
take part in sports activities and give performances with ethnic
features.
</P>
<P>
"However, we organize those who can to do some manual
labor. This will help some of them get rid of bad habits and
others to learn a certain skill so that they can find employment
after their prison term is up," Puncog said.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan prisons have left a good impression on many foreign
visitors, he said. He recalled a prison official from Finland
telling him that he was impressed by prisons in Beijing and Tibet
because prisoners there have very spacious rooms for living,
working, and receiving an education.
</P>
<P>
"He also told me that conditions in prisons in Lhasa are even
better than in some European jails," said Puncog. "Seeing is
believing, and any visitors to Tibetan prisons will not believe
Wolf's sheer nonsense."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970830.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Ethylene Project Begins Trial Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The 150,000-ton Guangzhou
Ethylene Project, one of the major projects in South China's
Guangdong Province, today is expected to go into trial production
today.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of raw materials is scheduled to be poured into
the ethylene splitting furnace, China Daily reported. It is
expected to produce the first Guangzhou-made ethylene about a week
later and be made into the final products a month later.
</P>
<P>
"The operation is a significant breakthrough for local
industry," said Miao Xinwen, an official from Guangzhou Ethylene
Co Ltd.
</P>
<P>
With construction having begun in 1993, the 7.9-billion-yuan
(957 million US dollars) project has been co-developed by China
Petro-chemical International Corp and Guangzhou city government.
</P>
<P>
Armed with nine complete sets of production equipment, it is
expected to produce more than 220,000 tons of polyethylene,
polypropylene, polystyrene and other plastic solid products a year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it will produce 140,000 tons of high-demand liquid
products, such as styrenes, methylbenzene and liquid gas.
</P>
<P>
"Local processing companies are bound to benefit greatly by
taking this billion of yuan's worth of business in petrochemical
processing industrial production," said the official.
</P>
<P>
Annual sales volume is expected to reach 2.4 billion yuan (289
million US dollars) to 2.5 billion yuan (301 million US dollars)
after the plants are put into formal production.
</P>
<P>
The ethylene project, located in Huangpu District, covers one
million square metres.
</P>
<P>
It includes an ethylene plant with an annual capacity of
115,000 tons, a polyethylene plant with an annual capacity of
100,000 tons, a polypropylene plant with an annual capacity of
70,000 tons, a styrene plant with an annual capacity of 80,000
tons and a polystyrene plant with an annual capacity of 50,000
tons.
</P>
<P>
The city government has been responsible for collecting 90
percent of all the investments regardless of their source.
</P>
<P>
More than 330 million US dollars worth of equipment and
technology has been imported from the United States, Japan and
France to guarantee that the project reaches an advanced world
production standard.
</P>
<P>
One of China's leading ethylene projects in the eighth
five-year plan period (1991-1995), the Guangzhou Ethylene Project
is part of raw materials in South China caused by fast economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
The other big ethylene project is the 300,000-ton one in
Maoming, southern Guangdong province, which can produce more than
890,000 tons of synthetic rubber, synthetic resin, chemical fibre
and organic chemical materials a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
