<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy to Repatriate Albanian Refugees Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Italy will soon start a staggered
repatriation of 10,000 Albanian refugees who fled to Italy from
civil strife in their own country earlier this year, sources from
the Italian government said today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a cabinet meeting today, which was
called to make new plans after a government decision to extend the
August 31 deadline for two months met with strong protests from
the opposition and the public.
</P>
<P>
The meeting set broad guidelines for a plan of imminent
repatriation of refugees; the plan will also receive further
discussion in the parliament later today.
</P>
<P>
The plan states that illegal Albanian immigrants will be sent
back gradually, with the first group leaving as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Some 17,000 Albanians fled to neighboring Italy since spring,
when a financial scandal triggered nationwide anarchy and plunged
the Balkan nation into a political and economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
A reported 7,000 have already returned to their own country,
but many say they want to stay on indefinitely. The Italian
government agreed Wednesday to an Albanian government's request to
extend the repatriation deadline, but the opposition strongly
opposed the decision and urged firmer action against the illegal
immigrants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
