<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Death Toll in Panama Reaches 869 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Panama has registered 1,469
cases of AIDS with 869 deaths since 1984, said a Health Ministry
official.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,469 cases of AIDS, 1,163 are men and 306 are women, or
average of about four infected men to one woman. About 696 men and
173 women have died, said Gladys Alicia Guerrero, director of the
Health Ministry's epidemiology division.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-five percent of the cases were infected as a result of
sexual contact, said the specialist, who added that there is
little available information locally about exercising preventive
measures.
</P>
<P>
Guerrero said the most often and easily-affected age group is
between the ages of 20-44. About 72.5 percent of the cases also
come from among the economically active and productive population.
</P>
<P>
Among the total number of individuals affected by AIDS, 300 are
over 45 years old, while 76 are under 15 years of age.
</P>
<P>
Carelessness in sexual activities also increases the risk of
transmitting the HIV virus that causes AIDS to the fetus in a
pregnant woman, Guerrero said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
