<HEADLINE> Venezuela Claims Sea Pollution Compensation From Greek Ship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The Venezuelan government has
lodged a claim for 60 million U.S. dollars in compensation from
the owners of a Greek ship that spilled 26,000 barrels of oil off
the western coast of Venezuela this February, local media reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Internal Affairs and the General Attorney
Office of Venezuela presented the claim to an international
pollution fund to cover the costs of cleaning up the oil, said
Lenin Herrera, president of the Maracaibo Lake Conservation
Institute, in the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Venezuelan fishermen have also demanded 130 million
dollars in compensation from the owners of the Greek ship known as
"Nisson Amorgos." 
