<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insurance Syndicate to Cover Satellite Launches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Nine Chinese property insurers
agreed on Friday to set up a syndicate that will specialize in
underwriting insurance policies for China's satellite launchings.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the China Aerospace Insurance Syndicate
will help strengthen the country's position in the global
commercial satellite launching market, today's China Daily quoted
Zhang Xinxia, president of China Great Wall Industry Corp (CGWIC)
as saying.
</P>
<P>
China has been using domestically-made rockets to launch
overseas satellites for 10 years and had a seven to nine percent
market share in the international launching market from 1990
through 1996. However, after a couple of failures during a two-year
period, the CGWIC lost several contracts, and international
insurers became very cautious about underwriting policies, the
Daily said.
</P>
<P>
The successful sending of a Philippine telecommunications
satellite into orbit earlier this month and domestic launches in
May and June have helped boost confidence and restore China's image
in the international market.
</P>
<P>
China's market share is expected to increase since CGWIC
expects to clinch two to four contracts for geosynchronous
transfer orbit launches each year after 1997.
</P>
<P>
The emergence of the syndicate reflects the financial sector's
strong confidence in the country's aerospace industry, Liu
Changbin, assistant to the president of China Aerospace Corp. said.
</P>
<P>
The syndicate includes the People's Insurance (Property) Company
of China Ltd (PICC Property), Pacific Insurance Co, Ping An
Insurance Co, Tian'an Insurance Co, Dazhong Insurance Co, Huatai
Insurance Co, Yong'an Insurance Co, Hua'an Insurance Co and
Xinjiang Corps Insurance Co.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
