<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Abide by WTO Magazine Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Canada said today that it will
abide by the World Trade Organization (WTO) ruling, which deals a
severe blow to its magazine industry.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the WTO, Canada also stressed that it will use
the 15-month grace period to find new methods to protect its
cultural industries.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, a WTO expert panel ruled that Canada
violated the free trade principle by implementing special tax
measures to block U.S. publishers to flood its market with the
so-called split-run magazines.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Canada lost an appeal of the ruling. In addition,
the WTO ruled Canada's postal subsidies for its magazines
contravened international trade practices.
</P>
<P>
The two WTO rulings have not only a potentially devastating
short-term effect on Canada's domestic magazines, but also have
serious implications for the whole of its cultural industry.
</P>
<P>
"The WTO decision is a body blow to Canadian culture but it
isn't just about magazines. It's about a broader U.S. policy to
boost its own entertainment industry abroad," said a spokesman of
the Council of Canadians.
</P>
<P>
Canadian government officials vowed that they will use the
15-month time to find a new solution to this old emotional
problem.
</P>
<P>
"This is something we are going to have to work with the
magazine industry to find some sort of alternative solution," said
a spokesman of the International Trade Department.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Heritage Minister Sheila Copps is reported to have met
several times recently with representatives of the magazine
industry.
</P>
<P>
"There are a whole whack of suggestions that have been coming
forward," said Heritage spokeswoman Cate McCready. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
