<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Current Account Deficit Up in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 29 (Xinhua) -- Canada's current account deficit
rose to 3.2 billion Canadian dollars (2.3 billion US dollars) in
the second quarter of this year, Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was the third consecutive quarter that Canada spent more
than it earned on goods, services, investment income and current
transfers, the federal statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
In the second quarter, Canada's surplus on goods was 5.4
billion Canadian dollars (3.8 billion US dollars), the lowest
level in three years.
</P>
<P>
The deficit on all other current account transactions fell to
8.6 billion Canadians dollars (6.1 billion USD), the second lowest
level in nearly five years.
</P>
<P>
During the second quarter, Canada's surplus on goods fell by
2.6 billion Canadian dollars (1.8 billion USD) as imports rose by
3.3 percent and exports fell by less than one percent. This was
the fourth quarter of substantial increases in imports.
</P>
<P>
The country's deficit on services, which was at 2.1 billion
Canadian dollars (1.5 billion USD), was at its lowest level this
decade, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, its deficit on investment income edged down to
6.5 billion Canadian dollars (4.6 billion USD), remaining within
the range of the two previous quarters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
