<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waigel: Germany to Hit Euro Budget Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 29 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
predicted today that Germany would be able to cut its budget
deficit to 3.0 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) this year,
just enough to qualify for the planned single European currency,
the Euro.
</P>
<P>
For 1998, Germany's budget deficit could be reduced further to
2.5 percent of GDP, Waigel added.
</P>
<P>
He also asserted that Germany would strictly apply the
membership standards for the Euro when the selection is made early
next year on which European Union (EU) states will be able to join
the club.
</P>
<P>
The EU is due to launch the Euro on January 1, 1999. Among the
qualification criteria, member states are required to bring their
budget deficit and overall national debt to less than three
percent and 60 percent respectively of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Decisions on which countries will be allowed to join the Euro
will be made early 1998, based on full economic data of 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
