<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: no Role of GIs in Arrest of Bosnia War Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
reaffirmed that there will be no role of the Stabilization Forces
(SFOR) in Bosnia in the arrest of the indicted war criminals in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
"That has been official policy from the beginning, that SFOR
troops -- it's not appropriate for SFOR troops to be involved
under the conditions laid out in the Dayton Accords, because
that's not their mission nor their training," said White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart made the statement on the island of Martha's Vineyard
in Massachussetts, where President Bill Clinton is vacationing.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think we have talked about doing things to strengthen
the War Crimes Tribunal process, but I'm not going to get into
how, where or when those things might happen," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Joint Chief of Staff John Shalikashivili said
Thursday that American soldiers would be ill-suited for the role
in the arrest of war suspects in the country.
</P>
<P>
"I have always argued that we should not ask our troops in
Bosnia to get involved in this," Shalikashivili said. "They are
not trained for that properly. That is not their task."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. fear that its some 8000 soldiers will be in danger if
they go to apprehend the indicted war criminals including former
Bosnian Serb leader Rodavan Karadzic. Two U.S. soldiers were
injured on Thursday in violent clashes with Bosnian Serbs in the
Bosnian town of Brcko. 
</P>
</TEXT>
