<HEADLINE> IFC To Finance $450 Mln Nickel Project in Venezuela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) today announced the signing of agreements under
which IFC will furnish a project finance package of 115 million
U.S. dollars for the Minera Loma de Niquel(MLdN) project of
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
MLdN will mine and smelt lateritic nickel ore to produce an
annual average 16,000 metric tons of nickel, principally for
export, over the estimated 27-year life of the deposit.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the mine, smelter and associated
infrastructure, with a total cost of estimated 450 million
dollars, are expected to be completed by early 2000.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion of financing, MLdN will owned indirectly 81.5
percent by Minorco S.A. of Luxembourg. Venezuela's Corporation
Caracas and Canada's Jordex Resources each hold 7.5 percent. IFC
will invest 74.5 million dollars of its own funds which include 65
million dollars in loan and acquirement of 3.5 percent of MLdN's
equity. A further 50 million dollars will be funded by banks
participating in an IFC-syndicated loan.
</P>
<P>
MLdN is the third mining investment IFC has made in partnership
with Minorco. Minorco and IFC are also shareholders in Codemin, a
Brazilian ferro-neckel producer, and in Quellaveco, a Peruvian
feasibility-stage copper project.
</P>
<P>
IFC is a member of the World Bank Group and the largest
multilateral source of equity and loan financing for private
sector projects in developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
