<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Backs Guatemalan Government Revenue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 29 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today
announced the approval of a 28.2 million U.S. dollar loan to
Guatemala to help finance the Tax Administration Technical
Assistance Project of Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to improve the revenue performance by
strengthening the tax administration system.
</P>
<P>
Guatemala's tax revenue ratio is among the lowest in Latin
America. Revenues have averaged between 6 and 9 percent of the GDP
over the last decade and registered 8.5 percent in 1996. These low
levels severely constrain public investment and social sector
spending with a significant impact on poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the recently signed Peace Accords the
government has undertaken to raise tax revenue to 10 percent of
GDP in 1998 and 11.4 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The total project costs are estimated at 40.3 million dollars.
In addition to the World Bank's funding, the balance will be
financed by the 9.2 million dollar government contribution as well
as the 1.5 million dollars USAID grant and 1.4 million dollar loan
from the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
