<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright to Visit Mideast Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will make her first trip to the Middle East on
September 9 to restore trust between the Palestinians and Israelis
so as to pull the peace process back on track, the State
Department announced on Friday.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin, in announcing her
maiden official visit to the Middle East, told reporters that the
secretary will "see what she and the United States can do to help
Israel and the Palestinians address the crisis of confidence" and
"explore with the parties how we can again find ways to move
forward towards a comprehensive peace.
</P>
<P>
Albright will also consult with the regional leaders concerned
"about a variety of other important issues, including the security
of the Persian Gulf, the issue of Iran, and the issue of Iraq,
Rubin added.
</P>
<P>
"Towards these objectives, the secretary will visit Israel, the
Palestinian Authority, Egypt, Jordan, Syria and Saudi Arabia,"
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Albright made the decision to pay her visit to the violent
conflict-ridden Middle East after a twin suicide bomb killed 16
people at a Jerusalem produce market on July 30, which made the
deteriorating situation in the region even worse.
</P>
<P>
However, Albright conditioned her trip to the region when some
progress there is made on security issue so that the way could be
paved for addressing "the crisis of confidence."
</P>
<P>
Now, "some progress has been made and there is a trend in the
right direction," Rubin explained why Albright has now decided to
go to the region.
</P>
<P>
Rubin played down expectations that the trip would achieved
instant results, saying the secretary of state "is not a magician.
She is a realist."
</P>
<P>
"The problems between the two parties (the Palestinians and
Israelis) are complex, they are deeply entrenched and they will
not be solved by one trip," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Albright spoke to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinians leader Yasser Arafat on Friday in preparation for the
trip.
</P>
<P>
When the secretary meets with Netanyahu and Arafat, she will
try to address a "crisis of confidence" that has kept Israel and
the Palestinians from resuming their negotiations, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
She will also promised direct U.S. participation in their
negotiations once resumed on the bases of trust between them.
</P>
<P>
She will also try to jump-start to the final settlement
negotiations, which include Palestinian demands for a state with
its capital in Jerusalem and the future of Jewish settlements on
land that the Arabs claim is theirs.
</P>
<P>
In Syria, Albright will try to revive the sporadic negotiations
with Israel which came to a standstill early last year.
</P>
<P>
The two countries negotiated for more than four years over an
Israeli withdrawal on the Golan Heights, saized from Syria in
1967, but reached no agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
