<HEADLINE> Foley Nominated to be Ambassador to Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 29 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Friday made his nomination of former House Speaker Thomas Foley to
be ambassador to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Foley, if confirmed by the Senate, would replace former Vice
President Walter Mondale in Japan. Mondale left Tokyo last
December, leaving the critical diplomatic post vacant.
</P>
<P>
Foley, a Democrat first elected to the House in 1964, is a
longtime advocate of trade with the Pacific rim. His home state of
Washington is a leading exporter to the region.
</P>
<P>
Foley was defeated in the 1994 Congress elections and his post
of the House speaker was taken over by Republican Newt Gingrich.
Since then, he has been associated with Aiken, Gump, Strauss,
Houer and Feld, a Washington, D.C. law firm.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also nominated former State Department spokesman
Nicholas Burns as ambassador to Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
